{"title_page": "Hugh of Ibelin", "text_new": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Hugh\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| alt               = \n| CoA               = \n| more              = \n| succession        = lord of Ibelin and Ramla\n| reign             = \n| predecessor       = [[Barisan of Ibelin]]\n| successor         = [[Baldwin of Ibelin]]\n| spouse            =\n| issue             = \n| full name         = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]\n| house-type        = \n| father            = [[Barisan of Ibelin]]\n| mother            = Helvis of Ramla\n| birth_date        = c. 1130-1133\n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1169/1171\n}}\n'''Hugh of Ibelin''' (c. 1130-1133 &ndash; 1169/1171) was an important noble in the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]] and was [[Lordship of Ramla#Lords/officials of Ramla|lord of Ramla]] from 1152-1169. \n\nHugh was the eldest son of [[Barisan of Ibelin]] and Helvis of Ramla. He was old enough to witness charters in 1148, as was his younger brother [[Baldwin of Ibelin]], which suggests he was born c. 1130-1133, as the male age of majority was fifteen. (H.E. Mayer has suggested a limited degree of competence may have been accepted from the age of eight, reducing his age, but the examples given of this are of males of the royal house, whose situation was somewhat different.) He was probably about ten years older than his youngest brother, [[Balian of Ibelin]].\n\nAfter his father Barisan died in 1150, Helvis married the [[Officers of the Kingdom of Jerusalem#Constables|Constable of Jerusalem]], [[Manasses of Hierges]], who was one of the strongest supporters of [[Queen Melisende]] in the power struggle against her son [[King Baldwin III]]. Manasses was exiled in 1152 when Baldwin was victorious in this struggle, allowing Hugh to inherit Ramla from his mother. Hugh took part in the [[Siege of Ascalon]] in 1153, and in 1157 was captured in battle at [[Banias]], being released probably the next year. In 1159 he visited the [[Principality of Antioch]] and met with [[Byzantine emperor]] [[Manuel I Comnenus]], who had arrived to assert his suzerainty over the principality. In 1163 Hugh married [[Agnes of Courtenay]] (1133 &ndash; 1184/1185), [[Lord of Toron|Lady of Toron]], the former wife of [[Amalric I of Jerusalem|King Amalric I]] and mother of [[Baldwin IV of Jerusalem|Baldwin IV]], daughter of [[Joscelin II of Edessa|Joscelin II de Courtenay, Count of Edessa]], by whom he had no issue. It is possible that Agnes had already been betrothed or married to him before 1157, date some say it was the one of the actual marriage but she married Amalric after Hugh was taken prisoner; Amalric was forced to divorce her before becoming King in 1163. \n\nHugh participated Amalric's [[Crusader invasion of Egypt|expedition to Egypt]] in 1167, and was responsible for building a bridge over the [[Nile]]. The crusaders allied with the sultan against [[Shirkuh]], the general of [[Nur ad-Din Zangi]] who was also fighting for control of Egypt, and Hugh was sent to protect [[Cairo]] along with the sultan's son Kamil. Hugh was the first crusader ever to see the sultan's palace. At the siege of [[Bilbeis]] during the same Egyptian campaign, according to Ibelin family tradition, Hugh's life was saved by [[Philip of Milly]] after breaking his leg and falling under his horse.<ref>[[Malcolm Barber]], \"The career of Philip of Nablus in the kingdom of Jerusalem,\" in ''The Experience of Crusading, vol. 2: Defining the Crusader Kingdom'', Peter Edbury and Jonathan Phillips, eds. (Cambridge University Press, 2003), pg. 61.</ref> Hugh died around 1169 during a [[pilgrimage]] to [[Santiago de Compostela]]. His territories of [[Lordship of Ibelin|Ibelin]] and [[Lordship of Ramla|Ramla]] passed to his brother [[Baldwin of Ibelin|Baldwin]].\n\nAnother [[Hugh of Ibelin (died 1238)|Hugh of Ibelin]] was the son of [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut]], and the grand-nephew of this Hugh.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[William of Tyre]], ''A History of Deeds Done Beyond the Sea''. E. A. Babcock and A. C. Krey, trans. Columbia University Press, 1943.\n*Peter W. Edbury, ''John of Ibelin and the Kingdom of Jerusalem''. Boydell Press, 1997.\n*H. E. Mayer, \"Carving Up Crusaders: The Early Ibelins and Ramlas\", in ''Outremer: Studies in the history of the Crusading Kingdom of Jerusalem presented to [[Joshua Prawer]]''. Yad Izhak Ben-Zvi Institute, 1982.\n*[[Steven Runciman]], ''A History of the Crusades, vol. II: The Kingdom of Jerusalem''. Cambridge University Press, 1952.\n\n[[Category:1130 births]]\n[[Category:12th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Crusades]]\n[[Category:Nobility of the Kingdom of Jerusalem|Ibelin, Hugh of]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:Lords of Ramla]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Hugh\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| alt               = \n| CoA               = \n| more              = \n| succession        = lord of Ramla\n| reign             = \n| predecessor       = Helvis of Ramla\n| successor         = \n| spouse            =\n| issue             = \n| full name         = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]\n| house-type        = \n| father            = [[Barisan of Ibelin]]\n| mother            = Helvis of Ramla\n| birth_date        = c. 1130-1133\n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1169/1171\n}}\n'''Hugh of Ibelin''' (c. 1130-1133 &ndash; 1169/1171) was an important noble in the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]] and was [[Lordship of Ramla#Lords/officials of Ramla|lord of Ramla]] from 1152-1169. \n\nHugh was the eldest son of [[Barisan of Ibelin]] and Helvis of Ramla. He was old enough to witness charters in 1148, as was his younger brother [[Baldwin of Ibelin]], which suggests he was born c. 1130-1133, as the male age of majority was fifteen. (H.E. Mayer has suggested a limited degree of competence may have been accepted from the age of eight, reducing his age, but the examples given of this are of males of the royal house, whose situation was somewhat different.) He was probably about ten years older than his youngest brother, [[Balian of Ibelin]].\n\nAfter his father Barisan died in 1150, Helvis married the [[Officers of the Kingdom of Jerusalem#Constables|Constable of Jerusalem]], [[Manasses of Hierges]], who was one of the strongest supporters of [[Queen Melisende]] in the power struggle against her son [[King Baldwin III]]. Manasses was exiled in 1152 when Baldwin was victorious in this struggle, allowing Hugh to inherit Ramla from his mother. Hugh took part in the [[Siege of Ascalon]] in 1153, and in 1157 was captured in battle at [[Banias]], being released probably the next year. In 1159 he visited the [[Principality of Antioch]] and met with [[Byzantine emperor]] [[Manuel I Comnenus]], who had arrived to assert his suzerainty over the principality. In 1163 Hugh married [[Agnes of Courtenay]] (1133 &ndash; 1184/1185), [[Lord of Toron|Lady of Toron]], the former wife of [[Amalric I of Jerusalem|King Amalric I]] and mother of [[Baldwin IV of Jerusalem|Baldwin IV]], daughter of [[Joscelin II of Edessa|Joscelin II de Courtenay, Count of Edessa]], by whom he had no issue. It is possible that Agnes had already been betrothed or married to him before 1157, date some say it was the one of the actual marriage but she married Amalric after Hugh was taken prisoner; Amalric was forced to divorce her before becoming King in 1163. \n\nHugh participated Amalric's [[Crusader invasion of Egypt|expedition to Egypt]] in 1167, and was responsible for building a bridge over the [[Nile]]. The crusaders allied with the sultan against [[Shirkuh]], the general of [[Nur ad-Din Zangi]] who was also fighting for control of Egypt, and Hugh was sent to protect [[Cairo]] along with the sultan's son Kamil. Hugh was the first crusader ever to see the sultan's palace. At the siege of [[Bilbeis]] during the same Egyptian campaign, according to Ibelin family tradition, Hugh's life was saved by [[Philip of Milly]] after breaking his leg and falling under his horse.<ref>[[Malcolm Barber]], \"The career of Philip of Nablus in the kingdom of Jerusalem,\" in ''The Experience of Crusading, vol. 2: Defining the Crusader Kingdom'', Peter Edbury and Jonathan Phillips, eds. (Cambridge University Press, 2003), pg. 61.</ref> Hugh died around 1169 during a [[pilgrimage]] to [[Santiago de Compostela]]. His territories of [[Lordship of Ibelin|Ibelin]] and [[Lordship of Ramla|Ramla]] passed to his brother [[Baldwin of Ibelin|Baldwin]].\n\nAnother [[Hugh of Ibelin (died 1238)|Hugh of Ibelin]] was the son of [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut]], and the grand-nephew of this Hugh.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[William of Tyre]], ''A History of Deeds Done Beyond the Sea''. E. A. Babcock and A. C. Krey, trans. Columbia University Press, 1943.\n*Peter W. Edbury, ''John of Ibelin and the Kingdom of Jerusalem''. Boydell Press, 1997.\n*H. E. Mayer, \"Carving Up Crusaders: The Early Ibelins and Ramlas\", in ''Outremer: Studies in the history of the Crusading Kingdom of Jerusalem presented to [[Joshua Prawer]]''. Yad Izhak Ben-Zvi Institute, 1982.\n*[[Steven Runciman]], ''A History of the Crusades, vol. II: The Kingdom of Jerusalem''. Cambridge University Press, 1952.\n\n[[Category:1130 births]]\n[[Category:12th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Crusades]]\n[[Category:Nobility of the Kingdom of Jerusalem|Ibelin, Hugh of]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:Lords of Ramla]]\n", "name_user": "ArisMethymna", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_of_Ibelin"}
{"title_page": "Roar (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 single by Katy Perry}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Roar\n| cover      = Katy Perry - Roar.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Katy Perry]]\n| album      = [[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]\n| released   = {{start date|2013|8|10}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   = March 2013\n| studio     = {{hlist|Luke\u2019s in the Boo {{small|([[Malibu, California]])}}|Playback Recording Studio {{small|([[Santa Barbara, California]])}}|[[Maratone Studios|MXM Studios]] {{small|([[Stockholm, Sweden]])}}|Secret Garden Studios {{small|([[Montecito, California]])}}}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[pop rock]]}}\n| length     = 3:42\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Katy Perry|[[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]|[[Max Martin]]|[[Bonnie McKee]]|[[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Dr. Luke]]|Max Martin|[[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Hummingbird Heartbeat]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Who You Love]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|CevxZvSJLk8|\"Roar\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Roar'''\" is a song by American singer [[Katy Perry]] for her fourth [[studio album]], ''[[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]'' (2013). It was released as the lead single from the record on August 10, 2013. Perry co-wrote the song with [[Bonnie McKee]] and its producers [[Dr. Luke]], [[Max Martin]], and [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]. It is a [[pop music|pop song]] containing elements of [[arena rock]] and lyrics centering on standing up for oneself and self-empowerment.\n\nTo promote the song, Perry performed under the [[Brooklyn Bridge]] at the end of the [[2013 MTV Video Music Awards]], on ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor Australia]]'', at the [[Sydney Opera House]] in late October 2013, and on the German TV show ''[[Schlag den Raab]]''. Grady Hall and Mark Kudsi directed the song's music video, which features Perry trying to adapt to the jungle and taming a [[tiger]] after surviving a plane crash. Though the song received generally mixed reviews, it was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]].\n\nThe song was a commercial success, topping charts in Australia, Austria, Canada, Ireland, Israel, Lebanon, New Zealand, Scotland, Slovenia, South Korea, the United Kingdom, and the United States. By the end of 2013, \"Roar\" had sold 9.9 million units (combined sales and track-equivalent streams) globally according to the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI). \"Roar\" has sold over 6 million copies in the US, over 1 million in the UK, and was Australia's best-selling single of 2013 with 560,000 copies sold within the year. When \"Roar\" was certified Diamond by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), Perry became the first artist to have three Diamond certified singles in the country, the other being \"Firework\" and \"Dark Horse\".\n\n==Production and composition==\n{{listen\n | pos          = right\n | filename     = Katy Perry - Roar.ogg\n | title        = \"Roar\"\n | description  = A 23 second sample of \"Roar\", a [[Pop music|pop]] song with influences of rock subgenres that lyrically, revolves around a theme of empowerment.\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nThe song was mixed by Serban Ghenea at MixStar Studios. \"Roar\" was recorded in four other studios: Luke's in the Boo, Playback Recording Studio and Secret Garden Studios, all located in the state of [[California]], as well as [[MXM Studios]] in [[Stockholm, Sweden]] Perry co-wrote the song with Bonnie McKee and its producers Dr. Luke, Max Martin, and Cirkut.<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Prism |titlelink=Prism (Katy Perry album) |others=[[Katy Perry]] |year=2013 |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Capitol Records]] |location=[[United States]]}}</ref> All its development took place in March 2013.<ref name=KatyOnPrism>{{cite web|last=Perry |first=Katy |title=Katy Perry - Prism |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dCIVlrUWMn8 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=November 4, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106164914/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dCIVlrUWMn8 |archivedate=January 6, 2014 }}</ref> McKee told [[MTV]] that \"Roar\" is \"kind of a 'pick yourself up and dust yourself off and keep going', female-empowerment song\" and \"kind of an epiphany song.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Vena, Jocelyn |title=Go Behind Katy Perry's 'Raw And Emotional' Prism Writing Sessions |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1716064/katy-perry-bonnie-mckee-prism.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=December 23, 2013 |date=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205010633/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1716064/katy-perry-bonnie-mckee-prism.jhtml |archivedate=December 5, 2013 }}</ref> Perry said she wrote the song after undergoing therapy, saying she was \"sick of keeping all these feelings inside and not speaking up for myself\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/grammys/news/1001829/behind-the-56th-grammy-awards-song-of-the-year-nominees/ |title=Behind The 56th GRAMMY Awards: Song Of The Year Nominees |publisher=CBS |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |date=January 23, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918134157/http://www.cbs.com/shows/grammys/news/1001829/behind-the-56th-grammy-awards-song-of-the-year-nominees/ |archivedate=September 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMusically, \"Roar\" is a [[pop music|pop song]] that features elements of [[arena rock]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/on-the-charts-katy-perry-and-lady-gaga-singles-duke-it-out-20130821 |title=On the Charts: Katy Perry and Lady Gaga Singles Duke It Out |first=Steve |last=Knopper |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911050626/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/on-the-charts-katy-perry-and-lady-gaga-singles-duke-it-out-20130821 |archivedate=September 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Slate1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/08/12/katy_perry_new_single_roar_latest_song_is_a_jock_jams_pastiche.html |title=Katy Perry new single \"Roar\": Latest song is a Jock Jams pastiche |first=Forrest |last=Wickman |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812194011/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/08/12/katy_perry_new_single_roar_latest_song_is_a_jock_jams_pastiche.html |archivedate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref> Throughout the song, Perry \"flexes diva-like vocals\", singing the lyric \"Hey!\" several times in a way resemblant of [[The Lumineers]].<ref name=\"rollingstone1\">{{cite web|first=Caryn |last=Ganz |title=Katy Perry - \"Roar\" |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/songreviews/roar-20130828 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=December 23, 2013 |date=August 28, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024073826/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/songreviews/roar-20130828 |archivedate=October 24, 2013 }}</ref> The song's [[instrumentation]] is composed of \"pounding\" pianos and \"booming\" bass drums.<ref name=\"rollingstone1\"/> According to the sheet music published by [[Alfred Music]]. on Musicnotes.com, \"Roar\" is composed in the key of [[B-flat major|B{{music|flat}} major]] and set in a [[time signature|{{music|time|4|4}} time signature]] at a moderate [[tempo]] of 90 [[beats per minute]]. Perry's vocal range spawns from the low note B{{music|flat}}<sub>3</sub> to the high note E{{music|flat}}<sub>5</sub>, while the music follows the [[chord progression]] of B{{music|flat}}\u2013Cm\u2013Gm\u2013E{{music|flat}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry \"Roar\" Sheet Music - Download & Print|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0122655&ref=google|publisher=Musicnotes.com|accessdate=December 23, 2013}}</ref> The song shares the theme of empowerment with Perry's single \"[[Firework (Katy Perry song)|Firework]]\".<ref name=\"Vibe\">{{cite web|last=Rogulewski |first=Charley |title=Katy Perry's New Single \"Roar\" Leaks |url=http://www.vibe.com/article/katy-perry-roar |work=Vibe magazine |accessdate=August 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812232434/http://www.vibe.com/article/katy-perry-roar |archivedate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"EnterntainmentWeeklyReview\">{{cite web|last=Atkinson |first=Katie |title=Katy Perry is back with a 'Roar' \u2014 hear her new single now |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/08/11/katy-perry-roar-single-listen/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=August 11, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814003016/http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/08/11/katy-perry-roar-single-listen/ |archivedate=August 14, 2013 }}</ref> Perry described the track as a song speaking about standing up for oneself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713155/katy-perry-roar-biggest-bully.jhtml |first=Christina |last=Garibaldi |publisher=MTV |title=Katy Perry Used To Be Her 'Biggest Bully' Before 'Roar' |date=August 27, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830021759/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713155/katy-perry-roar-biggest-bully.jhtml |archivedate=August 30, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nPerry announced \"Roar\" would be the first single from ''[[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]'' with the release of a video teaser featuring the singer burning a blue wig.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry Will 'Roar' Back Fiery New Track: Watch Her Tease! |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1711741/katy-perry-roar-new-single/ |publisher=MTV News |first=Jocelyn |last=Vena |accessdate=August 30, 2016 |date=August 2, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911110307/http://www.mtv.com/news/1711741/katy-perry-roar-new-single/ |archivedate=September 11, 2016 }}</ref> More video teasers were released onto [[YouTube]], showing Perry at a funeral with a coffin decorated with the singer's famous pink and white pinwheels dress,<ref name=\"bill\">{{cite web|date=August 6, 2013 |accessdate=December 1, 2013 |title=Katy Perry Buries Alter-Ego In New Teaser Clip |url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/katy-perry/387796-katy-perry-roar-second-teaser-the-third-coming-prism#3ChMSJcTbyzet0i0.99 |publisher=[[MTV]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204024149/http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/katy-perry/387796-katy-perry-roar-second-teaser-the-third-coming-prism |archivedate=December 4, 2013 }}</ref> and entering a recording booth while dressed with a \"throwback\" jacket featured in the single's cover art,<ref name=\"Williott\">{{cite web|last=Williott |first=Carl |title=Katy Perry Rocks \"Roar\" Jacket In Latest Teaser: Hear Another Snippet Of The Song |url=http://www.idolator.com/7476606/katy-perry-roar-teaser-snippet-jacket |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |date=August 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 1, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203022359/http://www.idolator.com/7476606/katy-perry-roar-teaser-snippet-jacket |archivedate=December 3, 2013 }}</ref> which was revealed on August 8, 2013.<ref name=\"Williott\"/> It features a tiger print border around Perry, who wears a blue [[Japan]]ese silk [[sukajan]] jacket, with the image of a tiger printed on its back.<ref name=\"style\">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' Single Cover Style Is Very Lisa Frank Meets 'Drive' |url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/08/08/katy-perry-roar-cover/ |last=Keirans |first=Maeve |publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=August 8, 2013 |date=August 8, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813123417/http://style.mtv.com/2013/08/08/katy-perry-roar-cover |archivedate=August 13, 2013 }}</ref> On the same day of the song's digital release, a lyric video for it, produced by Joe Humpay, [[Aya Tanimura]], Tim Zimmer, and Tuan Le, was released onto YouTube. It primarily shows Perry doing daily activities such as eating breakfast, going to the bathroom, and taking a bath, while texting the lyrics of \"Roar\" to friends. Some words are substituted with various [[Emoji]] characters.<ref name=\"Video\">{{cite web|last=Moraski |first=Lauren |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57598116/watch-katy-perrys-emoticon-lyric-video-for-roar/ |title=Watch: Katy Perry's emoticon lyric video for \"Roar\" |publisher=CBS News |date=August 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812175316/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57598116/watch-katy-perrys-emoticon-lyric-video-for-roar/ |archivedate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mallenbaum |first=Carly |title=Katy Perry releases 'emoticon' video for 'Roar' |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/08/12/katy-perry-roar-emoticon/2642249/ |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=August 12, 2013 |date=August 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815063522/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/08/12/katy-perry-roar-emoticon/2642249/ |archivedate=August 15, 2013 }}</ref> It was target of plagiarism accusations by music producer [[Dillon Francis]], who felt it copied the concept of instant messaging from his video entitled \"Messages\".<ref name=\"Copy\">{{cite web|last=Reilly |first=Dan |title=Dillon Francis Says Katy Perry's 'Roar' Ripped Him Off, But She'll Play the VMAs Anyway |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/08/katy-perry-rip-off-dillon-francis-roar-video-vmas/ |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |accessdate=August 12, 2013 |date=August 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814135653/https://www.spin.com/2013/08/katy-perry-rip-off-dillon-francis-roar-video-vmas/ |archivedate=August 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe first video teaser for \"Roar\" was released on August 2, 2013 along with an announcement that the American release was scheduled for August 12<ref>{{cite journal|title=Katy Perry Posts 'Roar' Teaser, Announces Single Release Date |journal=Billboard |accessdate=March 1, 2014 |date=August 2, 2013 |last=Gocobachi |first=Pam |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5638070/katy-perry-posts-roar-teaser-announces-single-release-date |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221105816/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5638070/katy-perry-posts-roar-teaser-announces-single-release-date |archivedate=February 21, 2014 }}</ref> with a subsequent release to [[Contemporary hit radio|mainstream radio]] on August 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814082751/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |archivedate=August 14, 2013 |title=Top 40/M Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group}}</ref> However, the song debuted two days earlier than expected by leaking on August 10.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 10, 2013 |title=Katy Perry's New Single 'Roar' Leaks: Listen |url=http://news.radio.com/2013/08/10/katy-perry-roar-leak/ |first=Courtney E. |last=Smith|publisher=Radio.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310083408/http://news.radio.com/2013/08/10/katy-perry-roar-leak/ |archivedate=March 10, 2014 |access-date=March 10, 2014 }}</ref> The UK release was originally scheduled for September 8, but on August 30 Perry announced the release date would be moved up to September 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry Brings Roar's UK Release Date Forward |url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/katy-perry/news/katy-perry-brings-roars-uk-release-date-forward |date=August 30, 2013 |accessdate=March 1, 2014 |publisher=MTV |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310091101/http://www.mtv.co.uk/katy-perry/news/katy-perry-brings-roars-uk-release-date-forward |archivedate=March 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Sara Bareilles.jpg|alt=|thumb|right|Many critics have noted similarities between \"Roar\" and [[Sara Bareilles]]'s \"[[Brave (Sara Bareilles song)|Brave]]\"]]\n\nMiriam Coleman from ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' appreciated the songs's \"easy poppy beat\" and its \"repeated refrains\", factors she believed contributed to make the song a \"determined note for the new album\".<ref name=\"RollingStone2\">{{cite web|last=Coleman |first=Miriam |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/katy-perry-drops-new-song-roar-20130811 |title=Katy Perry Drops New Song, 'Roar' |work=Rolling Stone |date=August 11, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812112437/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/katy-perry-drops-new-song-roar-20130811 |archivedate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref> James Montgomery of [[MTV]] described it as \"one of the more perfect pop songs to come down the pipeline in quite a while\". Gerrick D. Kennedy from ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' also gave a positive review, classifying \"Roar\" as a \"sweet, poppy confection with a bit of bite\".<ref name=\"Angeles\">{{cite news|last=Kennedy |first=Gerrick D. |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-to-katy-perry-roar-20130811,0,3722661.story |title=Listen to Katy Perry's new single 'Roar' |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812125251/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-to-katy-perry-roar-20130811%2C0%2C3722661.story |archivedate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"MTV2\">{{cite web|last=Montgomery |first=James |title=Katy Perry's 'Roar:' The Power Of Positive Thinking |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1712162/katy-perry-roar-release.jhtml |publisher=MTV News |accessdate=August 12, 2013 |date=August 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815053720/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1712162/katy-perry-roar-release.jhtml |archivedate=August 15, 2013 }}</ref> Melinda Newman from [[HitFix]] saw the song as a \"change of pace\" for Perry,<ref>{{cite web|last=Newman |first=Melinda |url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/katy-perrys-new-single-roar-in-full-is-a-fierce-fun-anthem-listen |title=Listen: Katy Perry's new single Roar in full, is a fierce, fun anthem |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=June 25, 2013 |accessdate=August 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813043029/http://www.hitfix.com/news/katy-perrys-new-single-roar-in-full-is-a-fierce-fun-anthem-listen |archivedate=August 13, 2013 }}</ref> whilst Andrew Hampp from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' believed it to be a return to the style of her album ''[[One of the Boys (Katy Perry album)|One of the Boys]]'', but criticized its tempo and its lyrics that \"rarely rise above easy clich\u00e9s and rhymes\".<ref name=\"Track\">{{cite web|last=Hampp |first=Andrew |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5645969/katy-perry-roar-track-review |title=Katy Perry, 'Roar: Track Review |publisher=Billboard. [[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814235701/http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5645969/katy-perry-roar-track-review |archivedate=August 14, 2013 }}</ref> Sal Cinquemani from ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' described the song as \"more of a yelp than a roar\".<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|last=Cinquemani |first=Sal |title=Listen to Katy Perry's \"Roar\" |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/10/listen-to-katy-perrys-roar |work=Slant Magazine |accessdate=August 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812120249/http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/10/listen-to-katy-perrys-roar |archivedate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nUpon the release of \"Roar\", many accused Perry of copying [[Sara Bareilles]]' \"[[Brave (Sara Bareilles song)|Brave]]\".<ref name=\"Angeles\"/><ref name=\"MusicMix\">{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Kyle |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/08/12/katy-perry-roar-sara-bareilles-brave/ |title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' sounds an awful lot like Sara Bareilles' 'Brave', says the Internet |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813013816/http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/08/12/katy-perry-roar-sara-bareilles-brave/ |archivedate=August 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Brave-ly Roar\">{{cite magazine|last=Pavlova |first=Victoria |title=Katy Perry And Sara Bareilles \"Brave\"-ly \"Roar\" In The Face Of Plagiarism Speculation |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/article/katy-perry-roar-sara-bareilles-brave-similarity_3810877 |magazine=Contactmusic.com |accessdate=August 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814112829/http://www.contactmusic.com/article/katy-perry-roar-sara-bareilles-brave-similarity_3810877 |archivedate=August 14, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Global News\">{{cite web|last=Kennedy |first=John R. |title=Katy Perry accused of being copy cat |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/778353/katy-perry-accused-of-being-copy-cat/ |publisher=Global News |accessdate=August 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815061329/http://globalnews.ca/news/778353/katy-perry-accused-of-being-copy-cat/ |archivedate=August 15, 2013 }}</ref> When Bareilles herself was asked about the controversy between the two songs, she responded: \"Katy's a friend of mine and we've known each other a really long time\", and was upset that there was a \"negative spin on two artists that are choosing to share positive messages.\" She also mentioned she had known about \"Roar\" before its release and stated \"If I'm not mad I don't know why anybody else is upset\".<ref name=\"Bareilles ABC\">{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles on 'Brave' vs. Katy Perry's 'Roar' |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/08/sara-bareilles-on-brave-vs-katy-perrys-roar/ |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=August 29, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901044247/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/08/sara-bareilles-on-brave-vs-katy-perrys-roar/ |archivedate=September 1, 2013 }}</ref> In response to the accusations, [[Dr. Luke]] tweeted on August 14, 2013: \"Roar was written and recorded before Brave came out.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=too bad..... |url=https://twitter.com/TheDoctorLuke/statuses/367577095125204993 |publisher=\"[[Twitter]]\" |accessdate=14 September 2013 |date=14 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921230348/https://twitter.com/TheDoctorLuke/statuses/367577095125204993 |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref> In direct response to the attention \"Brave\" received as a result of the plagiarism accusations, Bareilles' record label, [[Epic Records]], decided to promote \"Brave\" to the [[Contemporary hit radio|mainstream pop]] [[radio format]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Trust |first=Gary |title=Weekly Chart Notes: The 27 Songs To Spend At Least 10 Weeks Atop The Hot 100 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5657724/weekly-chart-notes-the-27-songs-to-spend-at-least-10-weeks-atop-the-hot-100 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=August 16, 2013 |accessdate=August 30, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827063735/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5657724/weekly-chart-notes-the-27-songs-to-spend-at-least-10-weeks-atop-the-hot-100 |archivedate=August 27, 2013 }}</ref>eqreqwreqwer\n\n==Commercial performance==\n===North America===\nOn the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], the song debuted at number 85 on the week-ending August 24, 2013 due to radio airplay.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5650672/robin-thicke-leads-hot-100-for-10th-week-katy-perrys-roar-debuts |work=Billboard |title=Robin Thicke Leads Hot 100 For 10th Week, Katy Perry's 'Roar' Debuts |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=August 14, 2013 |accessdate=August 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816033503/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5650672/robin-thicke-leads-hot-100-for-10th-week-katy-perrys-roar-debuts |archivedate=August 16, 2013 }}</ref> The following week, during its first week on sale, \"Roar\" sold 557,000 digital copies, earning Perry the highest first-week sales numbers of 2013 and also her biggest digital song sales week ever, breaking her previous record held by \"[[Firework (song)|Firework]]\", which sold 509,000 digital copies for the week ending January 8, 2011.<ref name=\"roar\">{{cite news|first=Keith |last=Caulfield |title=Luke Bryan Nets No. 1 Album, Katy Perry's 'Roar' Tops Digital Songs |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5659205/luke-bryan-nets-no-1-album-katy-perrys-roar-tops-digital-songs |work=Billboard |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 21, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821153153/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5659205/luke-bryan-nets-no-1-album-katy-perrys-roar-tops-digital-songs |archivedate=August 21, 2013 }}</ref> The song soared eighty-three positions to number two in its second week, kept from the top spot by only [[Robin Thicke]]'s \"[[Blurred Lines]]\", while becoming Perry's twelfth top-ten hit single in the United States, and her ninth consecutive single to peak within the top three on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5660927/robin-thicke-no-1-katy-perry-no-2-on-hot-100 |work=Billboard |title=Robin Thicke No. 1, Katy Perry No. 2 On Hot 100 |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=August 21, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821172152/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5660927/robin-thicke-no-1-katy-perry-no-2-on-hot-100 |archivedate=August 21, 2013 }}</ref> After another week at number two, \"Roar\" reached number one for the chart dated September 4, 2013, becoming Perry's eighth number one on the Hot 100 and her ninth [[Hot Digital Songs|digital number-one single]], after selling 448,000 copies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5680131/katy-perry-dethrones-robin-thicke-atop-hot-100 |work=Billboard |title=Katy Perry Dethrones Robin Thicke Atop Hot 100 |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=September 4, 2013 |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906163801/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5680131/katy-perry-dethrones-robin-thicke-atop-hot-100 |archivedate=September 6, 2013 }}</ref> \"Roar\" spent a total two weeks at number one before it was surpassed by [[Miley Cyrus]]' \"[[Wrecking Ball (Miley Cyrus song)|Wrecking Ball]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695590/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-swings-to-top-of-hot-100 |work=Billboard |title=Miley Cyrus' 'Wrecking Ball' Swings Atop Hot 100 |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=September 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920000156/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695590/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-swings-to-top-of-hot-100 |archivedate=September 20, 2013 }}</ref> On its seventh frame, the song moved 2-1 (peak audience impressions of 159 million) and became Perry's sixth number one on the [[Hot 100 Airplay (Radio Songs)|''Billboard'' Hot 100 Airplay]], as well as becoming her fastest climb to the top position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5733088/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-spends-second-week-atop-hot-100 |title=Miley Cyrus' 'Wrecking Ball' Spends Second Week Atop Hot 100 |date=September 25, 2013 |work=Billboard |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925202218/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5733088/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-spends-second-week-atop-hot-100 |archivedate=September 25, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/katy-perry-becomes-first-artist-to-earn-three-riaa-diamond-song-awards/068914|title=Katy Perry becomes first artist to earn three RIAA Diamond Song Awards|website=www.musicweek.com}}</ref>\n\n\"Roar\" also reached number one on both the US [[Mainstream Top 40]] and [[Adult Pop Songs]]. The number-one position on the ''[[Pop Songs]]'' chart gave Perry her tenth number one, tying her with [[Rihanna]] for the most number ones on the airplay-based chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695476/katy-perry-ties-for-most-pop-songs-no-1s |title=Katy Perry Ties For Most Pop Songs No. 1s |accessdate=September 16, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918173552/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695476/katy-perry-ties-for-most-pop-songs-no-1s |archivedate=September 18, 2013 }}</ref> The number-one position on the ''Adult Pop Songs'' chart also gave Perry multiple milestones; it became her eighth chart topper, tying her with [[Maroon 5]] and [[Pink (singer)|P!nk]] as the act with the most number-ones there. It also made the fastest ascension to the top spot; a record previously held by Perry's own single \"[[California Gurls]]\" (2010).<ref name=\"Britney\"/> It also set airplay records in both of the charts, by becoming the most weekly-played song in history, with 16,065 and 5,309 plays per week, respectively.<ref name=BillboardPDF>{{cite web|last=Trust |first=Gary |title=Miley Cyrus, Paramore Reach Top 10; Lorde Leaps To History |url=http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/TFMm1007.pdf |work=Billboard |accessdate=October 7, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019152413/http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/TFMm1007.pdf |archivedate=October 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe song has also reached the top spot on both the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult contemporary chart]] and [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name=\"Britney\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5719511/chart-highlights-britney-spears-bows-katy-perry-lady-gaga-leap-to-no-1 |title=Britney Spears Bows, Katy Perry, Lady Gaga Leap To No. 1 |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=September 23, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013 |work=Billboard |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925051118/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5719511/chart-highlights-britney-spears-bows-katy-perry-lady-gaga-leap-to-no-1 |archivedate=September 25, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/TFMm0923.pdf |title=Spears\u2019 \u2018Work\u2019 Is Just Beginning; Perry, Drake Score New No. 1s |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=September 23, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013 |work=Billboard |format=PDF |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927213630/http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/TFMm0923.pdf |archivedate=September 27, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/5762990/diplo-paris-hilton-lady-gaga-debut-on-dance-charts |title=Diplo, Paris Hilton, Lady Gaga Debut On Dance Charts |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 17, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ko1R07KA?url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/5762990/diplo-paris-hilton-lady-gaga-debut-on-dance-charts |archivedate=September 26, 2016 }}</ref> In addition to this, the track also reached number one on both the [[On-Demand Songs|On Demand]] and [[Streaming Songs|Streaming]] charts, with a weekly peak of 2.1 million and 12 million, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5680131/katy-perry-dethrones-robin-thicke-atop-hot-100 |title=Katy Perry Dethrones Robin Thicke Atop Hot 10 |work=Billboard |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906163801/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5680131/katy-perry-dethrones-robin-thicke-atop-hot-100 |archivedate=September 6, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"streaming\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5687387/katy-perrys-roar-rules-hot-100-for-second-week-lorde-reaches-top-3 |work=Billboard |title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' Rules Hot 100 For Second Week, Lorde Reaches Top 3 |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=September 11, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913203748/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5687387/katy-perrys-roar-rules-hot-100-for-second-week-lorde-reaches-top-3 |archivedate=September 13, 2013 }}</ref> \"Roar\" surpassed digital sales of four million in its seventeenth week, faster than any other song in digital history. Its sales reached 4.41 million by the end of 2013, becoming the sixth best-seller of the year. Perry has eight of her songs with sales more than four million,including Firework (7.3 million); Roar (6,4 million); Dark Horse (6,3 million); E.T. (5,9 million); California Gurls (5,8 million); Hot N Cold (5,7 million); Teenage Dream (4,9 million)and I Kissed A Girl (4,7 million) the most for any artist.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grein |first=Paul |title=Chart Watch: \"The Monster\" Lives Up To Its Title |url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/music-news/chart-watch-monster-lives-title-013939655.html |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=December 12, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216154718/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/music-news/chart-watch-monster-lives-title-013939655.html |archivedate=December 16, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"sales 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5855151/justin-timberlakes-2020-2013s-best-selling-album-blurred-lines-top-song |title=Justin Timberlake's '20/20' 2013's Best Selling Album, 'Blurred Lines' Top Song |first=Keith |last=Caulfield |work=Billboard |date=January 2, 2014 |accessdate=January 2, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105134039/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5855151/justin-timberlakes-2020-2013s-best-selling-album-blurred-lines-top-song |archivedate=January 5, 2014 }}</ref> As of February 2017, the single has sold 6,400,000 copies in the US, and been certified Diamond by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), making Perry the first artist to have 3 singles with a Diamond certification in the country.<ref name=USsales2017>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7694308/ask-billboard-katy-perrys-career-song-album-sales |title=Ask Billboard: Katy Perry's Career Song & Album Sales |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=February 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222052835/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7694308/ask-billboard-katy-perrys-career-song-album-sales |archivedate=February 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 2013, \"Roar\" debuted at number one on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] on the strength of digital downloads.<ref name=\"canada\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-08-31/canadian-hot-100 |title=Canadian Hot 100: August 31, 2013 |work=Billboard |date=August 31, 2013 |accessdate=August 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608192242/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-08-31/canadian-hot-100 |archivedate=June 8, 2014 }}</ref> In doing so, it became only the eleventh song to debut at number one on the chart, and it also became Perry's third number-one debut, making her the artist with most number-one debuts at the time.<ref name=\"canada\" /> It also became Perry's ninth Canadian Hot 100 number one, breaking the tie she shared with Rihanna for the most chart toppers. It has so far spent five non-consecutive weeks atop the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-05/canadian-hot-100 |title=Canadian Hot 100 |work=Billboard |date=October 5, 2013 |accessdate=September 26, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131123042038/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-05/canadian-hot-100 |archivedate=November 23, 2013 }}</ref> \"Roar\" was also in the top of the [[List of number-one digital songs of 2013 (Canada)|Canadian Digital Chart]] for three non-consecutive weeks; there, it was Perry's sixth number-one single.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musiccanada.com/Top20Digital.aspx?scid=65122 |title=Digital Tracks |work=Music Canada |publisher=Nielsen SoundScan Charts |date=September 11, 2013 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930015653/http://www.musiccanada.com/Top20Digital.aspx?scid=65122 |archivedate=September 30, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In Mexico, it reached number one on the [[Monitor Latino]] English-language airplay chart.<ref name=\"RadioNotas\">{{cite web |url=http://monitorlatino.com.mx//Charts/Ingles93020131062013.html |work=[[Monitor Latino]] |publisher=RadioNotas |accessdate=October 6, 2013 |title=Top 20 Ingles: Del 30 de Septiembre al 6 de Octubre del 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015102611/http://monitorlatino.com.mx//Charts/Ingles93020131062013.html |archivedate=October 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Europe, Oceania and Asia===\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Roar\" entered at number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on September 8, 2013, selling 179,500 copies in its first week and ending the prolonged number-one run of [[Ellie Goulding]]'s \"[[Burn (Ellie Goulding song)|Burn]]\". The song became Perry's fourth UK number-one single.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/katy-perry-roars-to-the-top-of-the-official-singles-chart-2475/ |title=Katy Perry Roars to the top of the Official Singles Chart |publisher=Officialcharts.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012014319/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/katy-perry-roars-to-the-top-of-the-official-singles-chart-2475/ |archivedate=October 12, 2013 }}</ref> The single spent two weeks atop the chart before being succeeded by \"[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]\" by [[Jason Derulo]] ft. [[2 Chainz]]. The song also debuted atop the adjacent UK chart of Scotland and the [[Irish Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2013&year=2013&week=34 |title=GFK Chart-Track |publisher=Chart-track.co.uk |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012011534/http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2013&year=2013&week=34 |archivedate=October 12, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/22/2013-09-14/ |title=2013-09-14 Top 40 Scottish Singles Archive |publisher=Official Charts Company |date=September 14, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020021623/http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/22/2013-09-14 |archivedate=October 20, 2013 }}</ref> \"Roar\" was the 6th best-selling song of 2013 in the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-singles-of-2013-2709/ |title=The Official Top 40 Biggest Selling Singles Of 2013 |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223235852/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-selling-singles-of-2013__3658/ |archivedate=February 23, 2015 }}</ref> where it became her second single after \"Firework\" to sell over a million copies in January 2015, thus making Katy Perry one of only 18 artists ever to achieve more than one million sales in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/katy-perry-super-bowl-half-time-show-roar-one-million-sales-3453/ |title=Katy Perry's Roar hits one million UK sales ahead of Super Bowl Half Time Show |last=Copsey |first=Rob |date=January 31, 2015 |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=January 31, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131151559/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/katy-perry-super-bowl-half-time-show-roar-one-million-sales-3453/ |archivedate=January 31, 2015 }}</ref> It has sold 1,112,787 copies in the United Kingdom as of September 2017,<ref name=\"ukmillion2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-official-chart-millionaires-revealed__20459/|publisher=Official Charts Company|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=September 19, 2017|title=The UK's Official Chart 'millionaires' revealed|first=Rob|last=Copsey}}</ref> and has been certified 2x Platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI).<ref name=\"bpi\"/>\n\n[[File:Katy Perry - Super Bowl XLIX Halftime 04.jpg|thumb|right|Perry performing \"Roar\" during the [[Super Bowl XLIX halftime show]]]]\nThe song reached number four on the [[FIMI|Italian Singles Chart]], where it was eventually certified [[music certification|Platinum]] by the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]], for sales of over 15,000 digital copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fimi.it/archivio_certificazioni.php |title=FIMI - Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana - Certificazioni |publisher=Fimi.it |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006100124/http://www.fimi.it/archivio_certificazioni.php |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref> In Spain, the single peaked at number five on the sales chart, according to [[PROMUSICAE]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://www.spanishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=spanishcharts.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> In Austria, it became a number-one on the [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]], while in Germany and Switzerland it reached numbers two and three, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.de/song.asp?artist=Katy+Perry&title=Roar&cat=s&country=de |title=charts.de |publisher=charts.de |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://www.swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=swisscharts.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> In the Belgian [[Ultratop 50]], \"Roar\" peaked at number five in [[Flanders]] and number seven in [[Wallonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=ultratop.be |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927200433/http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy%20Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |archivedate=September 27, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=ultratop.be |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014005724/http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy%20Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |archivedate=October 14, 2013 }}</ref> In France the song peaked at number six.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=lescharts.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929161601/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy%20Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |archivedate=September 29, 2013 }}</ref> The single also reached the top five in Norway.<ref name=\"Norwegian singles chart\">{{cite web |url=http://lista.vg.no/liste/topp-20-single/1/dato/2013/uke/36 |title=Norwegian singles chart |date=September 6, 2013 |accessdate=September 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928011530/http://lista.vg.no/liste/topp-20-single/1/dato/2013/uke/36 |archivedate=September 28, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \"Roar\" found placings among the top-ten of the airplay charts in Czech Republic, Hungary, and Slovakia. Within the unofficial digital charts of Greece, Luxembourg and Portugal, compiled outside of the respective countries by ''Billboard'', \"Roar\" peaked at number two in both the Greece and Luxembourg charts and at number eight in the Portuguese chart.<ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-08-31/greece |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 13, 2013 |title=Greece Digital Songs - August 31, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916020330/http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-08-31/greece |archivedate=September 16, 2013 }}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-09-28/luxembourg-digital-songs |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=September 21, 2013 |title=Luxembourg Digital Songs - September 28, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229182840/http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-09-28/luxembourg-digital-songs |archivedate=December 29, 2013 }}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-08-24/portugal |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=August 24, 2013 |title=Portugal Digital Songs - August 24, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305075002/http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-08-24/portugal |archivedate=March 5, 2014 }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n\"Roar\" entered at the top of the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]] after just four days on sale, becoming Perry's ninth number-one single, second top debut and her eleventh top ten.<ref name=\"nz\"/> After less than five weeks, the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] certified the single [[Music certification|quadruple-platinum]], denoting sales exceeding 60,000 units.<ref name=\"rianz\"/> The song is listed as the 48th best-selling single of all time in New Zealand, making Perry the only singer to have the most entries, which including \"[[California Gurls]]\", \"[[Firework (song)|Firework]]\" and \"[[E.T. (song)|E.T.]]\".<ref>[https://charts.nz/bestall.asp charts.org.nz. - New Zealand charts portal] . Best Of All Time list. Retrieved 6 January 2014.</ref> In Australia, the song became Perry's third song to top the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] after \"I Kissed a Girl\" and \"California Gurls\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Katy Perry's ROAR Tops ARIA Singles Chart |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/41887/katy-perry%27s-roar-tops-aria-singles-chart?pos=0 |publisher=ARIA Music News |accessdate=August 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055713/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/41887/katy-perry%27s-roar-tops-aria-singles-chart?pos=0 |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref> It was the country's highest performing song of the year, topping the charts for 9 weeks and selling 560,000 copies by the end of 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Cameron |title=ARIA album charts: Pink and Katy Perry score highest sellers in Australia in 2013 |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/aria-album-charts-pink-and-katy-perry-score-highest-sellers-in-australia-in-2013/story-fnhiy8bj-1226796832354 |accessdate=October 30, 2017 |date=January 7, 2014 |newspaper=Perth Now |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020858/http://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/aria-album-charts-pink-and-katy-perry-score-highest-sellers-in-australia-in-2013/story-fnhiy8bj-1226796832354 |archivedate=November 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \"Roar\" has since been certified 11\u00d7 Platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA).<ref name=\"aria\"/> \"Roar\" peaked at number two in the [[Record Report|Venezuelan Pop Rock Chart]].<ref name=\"Record Report - Pop Rock General\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JFZnFQG2?url=http://www.recordreport.com.ve/publico/?i=poprock |title=Record Report - Pop Rock General |language=Spanish |url=http://www.recordreport.com.ve/publico/?i=poprock |date=August 31, 2013 |archivedate=August 30, 2013 |work=[[Record Report]] |publisher=R.R. Digital C.A. |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Record Report - Pop Rock General\" /> On the [[Gaon Chart]] of South Korea, it reached number one on the international chart.<ref name=\"Gaon Digital Chart\">{{cite web |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/digital_chart/index.php?nationGbn=E&current_year=&current_month=07&current_week=34&chart_Time=week |title=Gaon Digital Chart |date=August 17, 2013 |accessdate=August 22, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927123254/http://gaonchart.co.kr/digital_chart/index.php?nationGbn=E&current_year=&current_month=07&current_week=34&chart_Time=week |archivedate=September 27, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In Japan, the song entered the [[Japan Hot 100]] at number seven.<ref name=\"Japan Hot 100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305595/katy-perry/chart?f=848 |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |title=Japan Hot 100 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929050026/http://www.billboard.com/artist/305595/katy-perry/chart?f=848 |archivedate=September 29, 2013 }}</ref> The reached number one in both the [[Media Forest]] airplay chart in Israel, and the [[The Official Lebanese Top 20|Lebanese Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"mediaforest.biz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaforest.biz/WeeklyCharts/HistoryWeeklyCharts.aspx?year=2013&week=35e |work=Midia Forest |accessdate=June 13, 2013 |title=Israel International Chart - August 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927123825/http://www.mediaforest.biz/WeeklyCharts/HistoryWeeklyCharts.aspx?year=2013&week=35e |archivedate=September 27, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"olt1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olt20.com/Katy-Perry#fragment-2 |title=The Official Lebanese Top 20 \u2013 Katy Perry |publisher=Olt20.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019113704/http://www.olt20.com/Katy-Perry |archivedate=October 19, 2013 }}</ref> Similarly, in [[South Africa]], the song peaked at number two on the [[Entertainment Monitoring Africa|EMA]] airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=South African Airplay Top 10 |publisher=[[Entertainment Monitoring Africa]] |date=September 17, 2013 |url=http://www.sa-ema.com/index.php/charts-board/?keywords=2013-09-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054741/http://www.sa-ema.com/index.php/charts-board/?keywords=2013-09-17 |archivedate=September 21, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Russia, on the [[Russian Music Charts|Tophit Weekly General Airplay chart]] the song debuted at number 395 on August 25, 2013 and it has climbed the chart, peaking so far at number five on November 17, 2013.<ref name=\"tophitru.com\">[http://www.tophitru.com/cgi-bin/trackinfo.cgi?id=50218 \u041e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u044b \u0440\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445, \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u0432 \u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0435 TOPHIT.RU<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211205445/http://www.tophitru.com/cgi-bin/trackinfo.cgi?id=50218 |date=December 11, 2013 }}</ref> On the [[Russian Music Charts|Top Hit Weekly Audience Choice chart]], it peaked at number three on the issue dated October 27, 2013.<ref name=\"tophitru.com\"/> According to the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI), \"Roar\" sold 9.9 million units (combined sales and track-equivalent streams) globally throughout 2013 and was the fifth best-selling single of the year.<ref name=worldwidesalesifpi>{{cite web|title=IFPI Digital Music Report 2014 - Top global singles |url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/Digital-Music-Report-2014.pdf |publisher=[[IFPI]] |accessdate=July 27, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626030458/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/Digital-Music-Report-2014.pdf |archivedate=June 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nFilming of the music video for \"Roar\" began on August&nbsp;7, 2013 and ended on August&nbsp;9, 2013. The video was released on September&nbsp;5, 2013, directed by Grady Hall and Mark Kudsi, and filmed at the [[Los Angeles County Arboretum and Botanic Garden]].<ref name=\":40\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/41887/katy-perry%27s-roar-tops-aria-singles-chart?pos=0 |title=Katy Perry's ROAR Tops ARIA Singles Chart - ARIA Music News |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022075134/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/41887/katy-perry%27s-roar-tops-aria-singles-chart?pos=0 |archivedate=October 22, 2013 }}</ref> A 21-second teaser of the video had previously been uploaded on August 25, 2013.<ref name=\"RoarTeaser\">{{cite web|last=Perry |first=Katy |title=Roar: Queen of the Jungle (Music Video Preview) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yD_-C7Hn2Y |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=August 25, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501221708/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yD_-C7Hn2Y |archivedate=May 1, 2016 }}</ref> Nokia posted a two-minute [[Making-of|behind the scenes]] video on September 4, 2013.<ref name=\"BehindRoarScenes\">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry \"Roar\" - Official Nokia Exclusive Behind the Scenes |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8UUSB9iKIy8 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=September 4, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909025938/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8UUSB9iKIy8 |archivedate=September 9, 2013 }}</ref> On November 14, 2013, an extended 17-minute behind-the-scenes video was uploaded to [[Vevo]].<ref>{{YouTube|Z0Q8j3HJagE|Katy Perry - Making of the \"Roar\" Music Video}}</ref> Roar music video reached 3 billion views on February 6, 2020, making Katy Perry the first female artist to reach 3 billion views on the platform.\n\n===Synopsis===\nAt the beginning of the video, Perry and her boyfriend (played by actor and model Brian Nagel) have crashed their plane in the middle of the jungle. Perry shows signs of worry, while her boyfriend takes [[selfie|pictures of himself]] and dumps his bags on her to explore. As it turns to night, they wander through the jungle as he throws things back at her. Suddenly, he is attacked by a [[tiger]] and Perry dumps her bags and runs off screaming. She approaches a lake and is almost bitten by a [[crocodile]] when she tries to take a drink. She sits on a rock and ends up with a [[tarantula]] crawling on her. As she looks into the lake while singing the chorus, she sees a reflection of a [[tiger]] instead of herself. Behind her in the darkness there are dozens of pairs of blinking eyes, but they are revealed to be [[fireflies]] which fly around her before forming an image of a roaring tiger in the sky.\n\n[[File:Katy Perry-Roar video.jpg|thumb|left|Perry in the music video for \"Roar\" dressed as \"Queen of the Jungle\".]]\nPresumably a few days later, Perry has since made friends with a [[monkey]] and uses her [[stiletto heel]] to form a spear. She uses it to shoot a [[banana]], which she gives to the monkey. In another scene, she bathes in the lake, with the help of an [[elephant]] who sprays her with water from the lake using its trunk. Perry helps a [[crocodile]] by brushing its teeth using a toothbrush she has salvaged, and tries to reach her clothes which have been taken by the elephant. At night, she holds a torch and explores a cave. Inside, she watches an animated drawing on the wall in which humans try to kill a tiger with [[fire]]; attempting to burn it as it grows stronger and shooting [[spears]] which it sends firing back towards them with its roar. The next morning, Perry emerges from the [[cave]], wearing a leopard-print [[bikini]] top, a [[grass skirt]], laced up legs and bare feet, displaying a boost of confidence and holding the spear she made earlier. She stands on top of a [[waterfall]], overlooking the [[jungle]], and then swings across the sky on a [[vine]].\n\nWith the help of the monkey, Perry builds a [[cat toy]] that she uses to distract the tiger who killed her boyfriend earlier in the video. The two of them roar at each other until her roar [[Tame animal|tames]] the tiger as it sits in front of her submissively. Afterwards, she is shown sitting on a giant grass throne, wearing a [[flower]] crown as the rest of the jungle animals sit around her, including the tiger, monkey and elephant. The tiger is shown wearing a [[collar (animal)|collar]] that says \"Kitty Purry\", a reference to her real-life cat of the same name. Perry takes [[selfie]]s with the monkey on her boyfriend's [[Product placement|phone]], applies lipstick made from berry juice, and gives the elephant a pedicure. She then awakens from sleeping in the plane, leading the viewer to think all the previous events have just been a dream, but walks out of the plane still in the jungle, stretching her arms and yawning with the animals sitting around her.\n\n===Reception===\nUpon its release, the music video received mixed reviews from critics. [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] contributors Robbie Daw, Sam Lansky, and Carl Willott gave it mostly lackluster reviews. Daw considered that the release of such a \"safe\" video was a disappointment for Perry and expressed eagerness to her next single; while Lansky likened its \"edg[iness]\" to that of a \"woman's antiperspirant commercial\"; and the latter divided the video in what he considered to be of \"good cheesy\" and \"bad cheesy\": he highlighted the fake set, Perry's acting and the ending, but criticized the CGI, which he deemed \"dopey\", the product placement and Perry's \"overly literal roar-off with a tiger\". The only writer for the website that gave the visual a favorable review was Mike Wass, who appreciated the \"campy element[s]\" in it, while noting that it drew inspiration from the [[Doctor Jones#Music video|music video for \"Doctor Jones\"]] by the dance-pop group [[Aqua (band)|Aqua]]. In total, the reviews had an average score of approximately 6 out of 10.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wass, Mike |title=Pop Perspective: Katy Perry's \"Roar\" Video Reviewed By All Four Idolator Editors |url=http://www.idolator.com/7482925/pop-perspective-katy-perry-roar-video |work=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate=December 25, 2013 |date=September 6, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110145156/http://www.idolator.com/7482925/pop-perspective-katy-perry-roar-video |archivedate=January 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nJames Montgomery from [[MTV]] believed that the video drew inspiration from ''[[Sheena, Queen of the Jungle]]'' and stated the video did not take itself too seriously, describing it as \"[[Camp (style)|camp]]\".<ref name=\"mtvnews\">{{cite web|last=Montgomery |first=James |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713557/katy-perry-roar-music-video-premiere.jhtml |title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' Video: All Hail The Queen Of The Jungle |publisher=[[MTV.com|MTV News]] |accessdate=September 14, 2013 |date=September 5, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908042059/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713557/katy-perry-roar-music-video-premiere.jhtml |archivedate=September 8, 2013 }}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' writer Sal Cinquemani was neutral about the video, noting that although ''Prism'' was being billed as a departure for Perry, both \"Roar\" and its video were not.<ref>{{cite web|author=Cinquemani, Sal |title=Music Video: Katy Perry's \"Roar\" |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/05/music-video-katy-perry-roar |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |accessdate=December 25, 2013 |date=September 5, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907215257/http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/05/music-video-katy-perry-roar |archivedate=September 7, 2013 }}</ref> Perry was criticized by [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] for using exotic animals in the video for \"Roar\". Merrilee Burke from PETA stated: \"Animals used for entertainment endure horrific cruelty and suffer from extreme confinement and violent training methods.\" Burke also declared that the animals involved in the music video were allegedly provided by a company who was criticized by US officials.<ref name=\"peta\">{{cite web|last=Lockley |first=Hannah |url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/katy-perry-criticised-peta-using-endangered-animals-roar-135440982.html |title=Katy Perry Criticized By Peta For Using Endangered Animals In Roar Video |publisher=Yahoo OMG! UK |accessdate=September 14, 2013 |date=September 14, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922140005/http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/katy-perry-criticised-peta-using-endangered-animals-roar-135440982.html |archivedate=September 22, 2013 }}</ref> Perry responded by obtaining a letter from the [[American Humane Association]], which had representatives present at the three-day shoot. It stated that \"After reviewing the reports, we believe that the Guidelines for the Safe Use of Animals in Filmed Media were followed and that no animal was harmed in the making of this music video\".<ref name=\"katypeta\">{{cite web|last=Lewis |first=Hillary |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/entertainment/katy-perry-responds-peta-criticism-animal-use-roar-video-4B11180867 |title=Katy Perry responds to PETA criticism of animal use in 'Roar' video |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |date=September 17, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005173353/https://www.nbcnews.com/entertainment/katy-perry-responds-peta-criticism-animal-use-roar-video-4B11180867 |archivedate=October 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn July&nbsp;7, 2015, the music video for \"Roar\" became the fourth video to reach 1 billion views on Vevo, making Perry the first artist in history to have two music videos with 1 billion views.<ref name=\"vevo\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Vevo_AU/status/618208657797443584 |title=Katy Perry's \"Roar\" hits 1 billion |publisher=vevo |date=July 7, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308003039/https://twitter.com/Vevo_AU/status/618208657797443584 |archivedate=March 8, 2016 }}</ref> The music video for \"Roar\" is the [[List of most viewed YouTube videos|tenth most viewed YouTube video of all time]], and has received over 3.0 billion views as of February 2020, making her the first female artist in history to do so.<ref>{{cite web|title=Most Viewed Videos of All Time (Over 450M views) |url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLirAqAtl_h2r5g8xGajEwdXd3x1sZh8hC |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=July 7, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809182529/https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLirAqAtl_h2r5g8xGajEwdXd3x1sZh8hC |archivedate=August 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- align=center \n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"17\" scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| [[NRJ Music Awards]]\n| Favourite International Song\n| {{won}}\n|rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction double winners at NRJ Awards |url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/one-direction/news/one-direction-double-winners-at-nrj-awards/ |accessdate=December 16, 2015 |publisher=MTV News |date=December 15, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223001353/http://www.mtv.co.uk/one-direction/news/one-direction-double-winners-at-nrj-awards |archivedate=December 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[ASCAP Pop Music Awards]]\n| Most Performed Song\n| {{won}}\n|rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/popawards/2014/most_peformed_songs.aspx |title=ASCAP Awards 2014 \u2013 Most Performed Songs |publisher=American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers |accessdate=August 9, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424234635/http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/popawards/2014/most_peformed_songs.aspx |archivedate=April 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=4|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n| Top Hot 100 Song\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=4 style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|title=Billboard Music Awards 2014|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbma/winners|accessdate=June 16, 2015|work=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121183050/http://www.billboard.com/bbma/winners|archivedate=January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Top Digital Song\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Top Radio Song\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Top Streaming Song (Video)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BMI Awards]]\n| Award Winning Song\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/stevie_nicks_and_top_songwriters_honored_at_62nd_annual_bmi_pop_awards |title=Stevie Nicks and Top Songwriters Honored at 62nd Annual BMI Pop Awards |publisher=Broadcast Music, Inc. |date=May 14, 2014 |accessdate=May 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Grammy Awards]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammy-nominations-winners-list-story.html |date=January 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 14, 2015 |title=Grammys 2014: The complete list of nominees and winners |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304121852/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammy-nominations-winners-list-story.html |archivedate=March 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[MTV Video Music Awards Japan]]\n| Video of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|language=Japanese|url=http://www.mtvjapan.com/vmaj2014/jp-best-pop-video/|title=\u6700\u512a\u79c0\u30dd\u30c3\u30d7\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u8cde Best Pop Video|publisher=MTV Japan|accessdate=December 14, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730214907/http://www.mtvjapan.com/vmaj2014/jp-best-pop-video/|archivedate=July 30, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Female Video\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Nickelodeon Kids Choice Awards]]\n| Favourite Song\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=1 style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>\n{{cite news|first=Emily |last=Yahr |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2014/03/31/kids-choice-awards-really-arent-just-for-kids-anymore/ |title=Kids' Choice Awards really aren't just for kids anymore |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=June 23, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201141034/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2014/03/31/kids-choice-awards-really-arent-just-for-kids-anymore/ |archivedate=February 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Premios Juventud]]\n| Favourite Song Not In Spanish \n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/premios-juventud/ganadores/openpage/2014-04-23/musicapj2014-ganadores|title=Lista de Ganadores de Premios Juventud 2014 \u2013 Univision Musica|publisher=[[Univision]]|accessdate=December 16, 2015|language=Spanish|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130192928/http://musica.univision.com/premios-juventud/ganadores/openpage/2014-04-23/musicapj2014-ganadores|archivedate=January 30, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Radio Disney Music Awards]]\n| Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=1 style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>\n{{cite news|last1=Hochman |first1=David |title=Radio Disney Music Awards 2014: Full List Of Winners |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhochman/2014/04/27/radio-disney-music-awards-2014-full-list-of-winners/ |accessdate=June 22, 2015 |work=Forbes |date=April 27, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630053706/http://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhochman/2014/04/27/radio-disney-music-awards-2014-full-list-of-winners/ |archivedate=June 30, 2015 }}<br>\n{{cite web|url=http://blogs.disney.com/oh-my-disney/music/2014/02/22/just-announced-the-2014-rdma-categories-and-nominees/ |publisher=[[Disney.com]] |date=February 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 11, 2016 |title=Just Announced: The 2014 RDMA Categories and Nominees }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Promotion and live performances==\n[[File:Katy Perry live in Berlin (19836736840).jpg|thumb|Perry performing \"Roar\" in Berlin]]\nOn September 16, 2013, the song was unexpectedly used during player introductions by the [[2013 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] in their home opener against the [[Bengals\u2013Steelers rivalry|rival]] [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', to tie in the song's [[jungle]] theme with the [[Bengal tiger|team's nickname]]. Throughout the game, the song was also played sporadically during game breaks. Although the Bengals won the game 20-10, the song drew much criticism by Bengals fans and even some of the team's players. One Bengals fan even told the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' that [[Steeler Nation|Steeler fans]] sitting near him were laughing at the Bengals fans throughout the game; the Steelers themselves have used the [[Styx (band)|Styx]] song \"[[Renegade (Styx song)|Renegade]]\" frequently at [[Heinz Field]] since 2001.<ref name=steelers>{{Cite news | title = Steelers Turn To Power Of 'Renegade' To Fuel Defense: 'Oh Momma' Rallying Cry For Black And Gold| publisher = thepittsburghchannel.com| date = November 9, 2009 | url = http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/sports/21562637/detail.html|archivedate=November 23, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5lUNrH0FM?url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/sports/21562637/detail.html}}</ref> Four days after the game, the team publicly apologized, announcing that while the song would not be nixed from [[Paul Brown Stadium]]'s playlist completely, the team would use a [[hard rock]] or [[classic rock]] song for player introductions moving forward.<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry song nixed for intros |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9701089/cincinnati-bengals-tone-katy-perry-roar-fan-backlash |publisher=ESPN |date=September 21, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231005020/http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9701089/cincinnati-bengals-tone-katy-perry-roar-fan-backlash |archivedate=December 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n\"Roar\" was also used as the theme song of [[WTA number 1|world number 1]] tennis player [[Serena Williams]] during the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|2014 US Open Championships]]. Williams, dressed in a matching leopard-themed dress, won the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/tennis-busted-racquet/serena-williams-moves-on-to-semi-finals-at-u-s--open-022733455.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-01-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305095558/http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/tennis-busted-racquet/serena-williams-moves-on-to-semi-finals-at-u-s--open-022733455.html |archivedate=March 5, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2014/sep/07/serena-williams-v-caroline-wozniacki-us-open-womens-final-2014-live |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-12-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120084224/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2014/sep/07/serena-williams-v-caroline-wozniacki-us-open-womens-final-2014-live |archivedate=January 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nPerry first performed \"Roar\" at the [[2013 MTV Video Music Awards]], in a specially-made boxing ring under the [[Brooklyn Bridge]], at the end of the ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wickman |first=Kase |title=Katy Perry Makes Brooklyn 'Roar' With Epic VMA Finale |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713031/katy-perry-roar-vma-finale.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=December 1, 2013 |date=August 26, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203080632/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713031/katy-perry-roar-vma-finale.jhtml |archivedate=December 3, 2013 }}</ref> She performed the song on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on October 12, 2013.<ref name=\"snlarchives\">{{cite web|url=http://snlarchives.net/detail.php?i=201310128 |title=SNL Archives - Episodes - Details |work=The SNL Archives |last=Navaroli |first=Joel |accessdate=January 7, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108040052/http://snlarchives.net/detail.php?i=201310128 |archivedate=January 8, 2014 }}</ref> While hosting ''We Can Survive: Music for Life'' on October 23, 2013, she performed the song with [[Sara Bareilles]], [[Bonnie McKee]], [[Ellie Goulding]], [[Kacey Musgraves]], and duo [[Tegan and Sara]].<ref name=\"Hollywood Bowl\">{{cite web|last=Aguila |first=Justino |title=Katy Perry Hosts Famous Friends, Previews Next Tour at Hollywood Bowl: Live Review |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5770379/katy-perry-hosts-famous-friends-previews-next-tour-at-hollywood |work=Billboard |date=October 24, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624200053/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5770379/katy-perry-hosts-famous-friends-previews-next-tour-at-hollywood |archivedate=June 24, 2014 }}</ref> She also performed the song on the [[Australian]] version of ''[[The X Factor]]'' on October 28, 2013.<ref name=XFactorPrismSongs>{{cite web|last=Kevipod |first=Kevin |title=Katy Perry Performs \"Roar\" & \"Unconditionally\" on \"The X Factor Australia\" |url=http://www.directlyrics.com/katy-perry-performs-roar-uncoditionally-on-the-x-factor-australia-news.html |publisher=directlyrics.com |accessdate=October 28, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029205110/http://www.directlyrics.com/katy-perry-performs-roar-uncoditionally-on-the-x-factor-australia-news.html |archivedate=October 29, 2013 }}</ref> Perry then performed the song the following day at the [[Sydney Opera House]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Somosot |first=Janice |title=Katy Perry 'Roars' at the Sydney Opera House for Aussie Promo of 'PRISM' Album |url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/518022/20131030/katy-perry-sydney-opera-house-prism-aussie.htm |website=[[International Business Times]] |publisher=IBT |accessdate=December 17, 2014 |date=October 30, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223185649/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/518022/20131030/katy-perry-sydney-opera-house-prism-aussie.htm |archivedate=December 23, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She performed the song on German TV show ''[[Schlag den Raab]]'' on November 16, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schlag den Raab 43 vom 16. November 2013 |url=http://www.prosieben.de/tv/schlag-den-raab/episodenguide/143-schlag-den-raab-43-vom-16-november-2013 |publisher=ProSiebenSat1 Networld |author=ProSieben |date=November 16, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117224608/http://www.prosieben.de/tv/schlag-den-raab/episodenguide/143-schlag-den-raab-43-vom-16-november-2013 |archivedate=November 17, 2013 }}</ref> On December 14, 2013, Perry performed \"Roar\" at the [[NRJ Music Awards]], but suffered technical difficulties which resulted in her performance being stopped by the host halfway through who asked for it to be restarted. This led many to believe that Perry had initially been lip-syncing the performance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Katy Perry accused of lip-syncing \"Roar\" at NRJ Music Awards |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/katy-perry-accused-of-lipsynching-roar-at-the-nrj-music-awards-in-france/story-e6frfn09-1226785867582 |work=News.com.au |accessdate=January 21, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129003316/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/katy-perry-accused-of-lipsynching-roar-at-the-nrj-music-awards-in-france/story-e6frfn09-1226785867582 |archivedate=January 29, 2014 }}</ref> NRJ later released an apology to Perry, stating that she had been singing live but that the wrong mix of the song was played over her live vocals, which resulted in her being visually out of sync with the backing track.<ref name=\"nrj\">{{cite web|url=http://nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr/nomines-4519/artiste/actu/561-katy-perry.html?actu_id=306298_katy-perry-remporte-le-nrj-music-award-du-best-digital-moment- |title=KATY PERRY REMPORTE LE NRJ MUSIC AWARD DU BEST DIGITAL MOMENT ! |language=French |publisher=nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr |date=December 15, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113081742/http://nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr/nomines-4519/artiste/actu/561-katy-perry.html?actu_id=306298_katy-perry-remporte-le-nrj-music-award-du-best-digital-moment- |archivedate=January 13, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2015, Perry performed the song during the [[Super Bowl XLIX halftime show]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipshutz |first1=Jason |title=Katy Perry Shines During Super Bowl XLIX Halftime Show |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/super-bowl-2015/6458199/katy-perry-super-bowl-xlix-halftime-show-review |accessdate=February 1, 2015 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |agency=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=February 1, 2015 |location=United States |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203202853/http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/super-bowl-2015/6458199/katy-perry-super-bowl-xlix-halftime-show-review |archivedate=February 3, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, 2016, she performed it at the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Grant |first=Sarah |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/watch-katy-perry-rise-and-roar-for-hillary-clinton-at-dnc-w431537 |title=Watch Katy Perry 'Rise' and 'Roar' for Hillary Clinton at DNC |journal=Rolling Stone |date=July 28, 2016 |accessdate=July 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730152403/http://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/watch-katy-perry-rise-and-roar-for-hillary-clinton-at-dnc-w431537 |archivedate=July 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 27, 2017, Perry performed the song as her finale at BBC radio one's big weekend in Hull.\n\nOn June 4, 2017, Perry performed \"Roar\" at the [[One Love Manchester]] benefit concert for the victims of the [[Manchester Arena bombing]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Iasimone |first1=Ashley |title=One Love Manchester: Ariana Grande Opens Benefit Concert With 'Be Alright,' Joins Black Eyed Peas for 'Where Is the Love?' |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/concerts/7817600/ariana-grande-manchester-benefit-concert-live-stream-recap |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604230751/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/concerts/7817600/ariana-grande-manchester-benefit-concert-live-stream-recap |archivedate=June 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions and usage in media==\nIn 2013, the song was covered on the episode \"[[A Katy or a Gaga]]\" of the TV series ''[[Glee (TV Series)|Glee]]''. The song is also featured in the films ''[[Horrible Bosses 2]]'' and ''[[Baywatch (film)|Baywatch]].'' It has become the new entrance music for [[Amanda Nunes]].\n\nThe song was featured in the August 5th 2014 episode of [[British soap opera]] [[EastEnders]] during an uplifting scene that saw [[Mick Carter]] ([[Danny Dyer]]) overcome his fear of swimming, while being cheered on by his wife [[Linda Carter|Linda]] ([[Kellie Bright]]).\n\nIt is prominently featured in the pilot episode of the American television [[sitcom]] [[Imaginary Mary]] starring [[Jenna Elfman]] and broadcast on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television network.\n\n[[Rick Springfield]] has been performing the song on tour since 2014. It is also Brisbane Roar's theme song (go Roar).<ref>{{Citation|last=JW Stuff|title=Rick Springfield - Roar (Katy Perry Cover)|date=2014-06-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RNq5W-eDzEU|accessdate=2016-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe song is featured as free downloadable content on the dance rhythm game, ''[[Just Dance 2014]]''.\n\nThe song was featured on [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|seventh season]] of reality television show ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', when contestants Kennedy Davenport and [[Katya Zamolodchikova|Katya]] had to lip-sync to \"Roar\" in order to avoid elimination. Davenport survived the lip-sync battle, and Katya was controversially eliminated.\n\n==Formats and track listings==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = CD single<ref name=\"CDsingle\">{{cite AV media notes| title= Roar | id= 0602537537990 | others=[[Katy Perry]] | publisher=[[Capitol Records]] |date=2013 | type=CD cover }}</ref>\n| total_length    = 7:24\n| title1          = Roar\n| length1         = 3:42\n| title2          = Roar\n| note2           = Instrumental\n| length2         = 3:42\n}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from ''Prism'' album liner notes.<ref name=\"Notes\"/>\n* [[Katy Perry]]