<ref>[http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/lc.html PDS lightcurve data] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20060614093519/http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/lc.html |date=14 June 2006 }}</ref>\n| spectral_type=[[S-type asteroid|S]]\n| magnitude = 8.8<ref name=AstDys-Ariadne>{{cite web |title=AstDys (43) Ariadne Ephemerides |publisher=Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy |url=https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.1&n=43&oc=500&y0=2096&m0=6&d0=15&h0=0&mi0=0&y1=2096&m1=6&d1=15&h1=0&mi1=0&ti=1.0&tiu=days |accessdate=2010-06-26 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/68ktakzpj?url=http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.1 |archive-date=2012-06-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> to 13.42\n| abs_magnitude=7.93\n| albedo=0.274<ref name=\"IRAS\">[http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/astdata04/simps04/diamalb.tab Supplemental IRAS Minor Planet Survey] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20060623213811/http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/astdata04/simps04/diamalb.tab |date=23 June 2006 }}</ref>\n| angular_size = 0.11<!-- Horizons 2011-Jun-28 -->\u20130.025&Prime;\n}}\n'''Ariadne''' ([[minor planet designation]]: '''43 Adriane''') is a fairly large and bright [[main-belt]] [[asteroid]]. It is the second-largest member of the [[Flora family|Flora asteroid family]]. It was discovered by [[Norman Robert Pogson|N. R. Pogson]] on 15 April 1857 and named after the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] heroine [[Ariadne]].\n\n==Characteristics==\nAriadne is very elongate (almost twice as long as its smallest dimension) and probably bi-lobed<ref name=\"Tanga03\">{{cite journal |last=Tanga |first=P. |date=2003 |title=Asteroid observations with the Hubble Space Telescope |journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics |volume=401 |issue= 2|pages=733\u2013741 |doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20030032 |url=http://www.edpsciences.org/articles/aa/pdf/2003/14/aa3023.pdf |bibcode=2003A&A...401..733T|display-authors=etal}}</ref> or at least very angular. It is a [[Prograde and retrograde motion|retrograde]] rotator, although its pole points almost parallel to the ecliptic towards [[ecliptic coordinate system|ecliptic coordinates]] (\u03b2, \u03bb) = (\u221215\u00b0, 253\u00b0) with a 10\u00b0 uncertainty.<ref name=\"Kaasalainen02\">{{cite journal |last=Kaasalainen |first=M. |author2=Torppa, J. |author3=Piironen, J. |date=2002 |title=Models of Twenty Asteroids from Photometric Data |journal=Icarus |volume=159 |issue=2 |pages=369\u2013395 |doi=10.1006/icar.2002.6907 |url=http://www.rni.helsinki.fi/~mjk/IcarPIII.pdf |bibcode=2002Icar..159..369K}}</ref> This gives an [[axial tilt]] of about 105\u00b0.\n\n==Studies==\n43 Ariadne was in a study of asteroids using the Hubble [[Fine Guidance Sensor (HST)|FGS]].<ref name=\"Tanga 733\u2013741\">{{Cite journal|last=Tanga|first=P.|last2=Hestroffer|first2=D.|last3=Cellino|first3=A.|last4=Lattanzi|first4=M.|last5=Martino|first5=M. Di|last6=Zappal\u00e0|first6=V.|date=2003-04-01|title=Asteroid observations with the Hubble Space Telescope FGS|url=https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/abs/2003/14/aa3023/aa3023.html|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|language=en|volume=401|issue=2|pages=733\u2013741|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20030032|issn=0004-6361|bibcode=2003A&A...401..733T}}</ref> Asteroids studied include [[63 Ausonia|(63) Ausonia]],  [[15 Eunomia|(15) Eunomia]], (43) Ariadne, [[44 Nysa|(44) Nysa]], and [[624 Hektor|(624) Hektor]].<ref name=\"Tanga 733\u2013741\"/>\n\n==Trivia==\n* For reasons unknown, \"Asteroid 43 Ariadne\" was included in a list of names of supporters of the [[NASA]] [[spacecraft]] [[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust]] that was stored on a microchip within the spacecraft.\n* The maximum apparent size of Ariadne is equivalent to the maximum apparent size of [[Pluto#Physical characteristics|Pluto]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Carry2012\">{{Citation\n | first1    = B.\n | last1     = Carry\n | title     = Density of asteroids\n | work      = Planetary and Space Science\n | volume    = 73\n | pages     = 98\u2013118\n | date      = December 2012\n | doi       = 10.1016/j.pss.2012.03.009\n | bibcode   = 2012P&SS...73...98C\n | postscript= .\n | arxiv     = 1203.4336 }} See Table 1.</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041015112635/http://www.rni.helsinki.fi/~mjk/IcarPIII.pdf shape model deduced from lightcurve]\n* [http://www.edpsciences.org/articles/aa/pdf/2003/14/aa3023.pdf?access=ok bi-lobed shape model from Hubble lightcurves] {{dead link|date=April 2019}}\n* {{AstDys|43}}\n* {{JPL small body}}\n\n{{Minor planets navigator |42 Isis |number=43 |44 Nysa}}\n{{Small Solar System bodies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:000043}}\n[[Category:Flora asteroids]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by Norman Pogson|Ariadne]]\n[[Category:Minor planets named from Greek mythology|Ariadne]]\n[[Category:Named minor planets|Ariadne]]\n[[Category:S-type asteroids (Tholen)]]\n[[Category:Sk-type asteroids (SMASS)]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1857|18570415]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox planet\n| minorplanet = yes\n| bgcolour=#D6D6D6\n| name=43 Ariadne\n| image=43Ariadne (Lightcurve Inversion).png\n| image_size = 265\n| caption=A three-dimensional model of 43 Ariadne based on its [[light curve]]\n| discoverer=[[Norman Robert Pogson|N. R. Pogson]]\n| discovered=April 15, 1857\n| mpc_name=(43) Ariadne\n| pronounced={{IPAc-en|\u00e6r|i|\u02c8|\u00e6|d|n|i\u02d0}}<ref>Noah Webster (1884) ''A Practical Dictionary of the English Language''</ref>\n| adjective=Ariadnean, Ariadnian {{IPAc-en|\u00e6r|i|\u02c8|\u00e6|d|n|i|\u0259|n}}\n| alt_names=\n| named_after = [[Ariadne]]\n| mp_category=[[Asteroid belt|Main belt]] ([[Flora family]])\n| epoch=November 26, 2005 ([[Julian day|JD]] 2453700.5)\n| semimajor=329.646 Gm (2.204 [[Astronomical unit|AU]])\n| perihelion=274.339 Gm (1.834 AU)\n| aphelion=384.954 Gm (2.573 AU)\n| eccentricity=0.168\n| period=1194.766 d (3.27 [[Julian year (astronomy)|a]])\n| inclination=3.464\u00b0\n| asc_node=264.937\u00b0\n| arg_peri=15.948\u00b0\n| mean_anomaly=101.582\u00b0\n| dimensions=95\u00d760\u00d750 km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/simps.html |title=IRAS Minor Planet Survey (IMPS)|accessdate=2005-12-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20051211134758/http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/simps.html |archivedate=2005-12-11 }}</ref><ref name=\"Kaasalainen02\" /><ref name=\"Tanga03\" />\n| mass={{nowrap|(1.21 \u00b1 0.22) \u00d7 10<sup>18</sup> kg<ref name=\"Carry2012\"/>}}\n| density=~2.7 g/cm\u00b3 ''(estimate)''<ref name=\"Krasinsky02\">{{cite journal |last=Krasinsky |first=G. A. |year=2002 |title=Hidden Mass in the Asteroid Belt |journal=Icarus |volume=158 |issue=1 |pages=98\u2013105 |doi=10.1006/icar.2002.6837 |bibcode=2002Icar..158...98K|display-authors=etal}}</ref><br />8.99 \u00b1 2.57<ref name=\"Carry2012\"/> g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| rotation=0.2401 d<ref>[http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/lc.html PDS lightcurve data] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20060614093519/http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/lc.html |date=June 14, 2006 }}</ref>\n| spectral_type=[[S-type asteroid|S]]\n| magnitude = 8.8<ref name=AstDys-Ariadne>{{cite web |title=AstDys (43) Ariadne Ephemerides |publisher=Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy |url=https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.1&n=43&oc=500&y0=2096&m0=6&d0=15&h0=0&mi0=0&y1=2096&m1=6&d1=15&h1=0&mi1=0&ti=1.0&tiu=days |accessdate=2010-06-26 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/68ktakzpj?url=http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.1 |archive-date=2012-06-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> to 13.42\n| abs_magnitude=7.93\n| albedo=0.274<ref name=\"IRAS\">[http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/astdata04/simps04/diamalb.tab Supplemental IRAS Minor Planet Survey] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.today/20060623213811/http://www.psi.edu/pds/archive/astdata04/simps04/diamalb.tab |date=June 23, 2006 }}</ref>\n| angular_size = 0.11&Prime; <!-- Horizons 2011-Jun-28 --> to 0.025&Prime;\n}}\n\n'''Ariadne''' ([[minor planet designation]]: '''43 Adriane''') is a fairly large and bright [[main-belt]] [[asteroid]]. It is the second-largest member of the [[Flora family|Flora asteroid family]]. It was discovered by [[Norman Robert Pogson|N. R. Pogson]] on April 15, 1857, and named after the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] heroine [[Ariadne]].\n\n==Characteristics==\nAriadne is very elongate (almost twice as long as its smallest dimension) and probably bi-lobed<ref name=\"Tanga03\">{{cite journal |last=Tanga |first=P. |date=2003 |title=Asteroid observations with the Hubble Space Telescope |journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics |volume=401 |issue= 2|pages=733\u2013741 |doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20030032 |url=http://www.edpsciences.org/articles/aa/pdf/2003/14/aa3023.pdf |bibcode=2003A&A...401..733T|display-authors=etal}}</ref> or at least very angular. It is a [[Prograde and retrograde motion|retrograde]] rotator, although its pole points almost parallel to the ecliptic towards [[ecliptic coordinate system|ecliptic coordinates]] (\u03b2, \u03bb) = (\u221215\u00b0, 253\u00b0) with a 10\u00b0 uncertainty.<ref name=\"Kaasalainen02\">{{cite journal |last=Kaasalainen |first=M. |author2=Torppa, J. |author3=Piironen, J. |date=2002 |title=Models of Twenty Asteroids from Photometric Data |journal=Icarus |volume=159 |issue=2 |pages=369\u2013395 |doi=10.1006/icar.2002.6907 |url=http://www.rni.helsinki.fi/~mjk/IcarPIII.pdf |bibcode=2002Icar..159..369K}}</ref> This gives an [[axial tilt]] of about 105\u00b0.\n\n==Studies==\n43 Ariadne was in a study of asteroids using the Hubble [[Fine Guidance Sensor (HST)|FGS]].<ref name=\"Tanga 733\u2013741\">{{Cite journal|last=Tanga|first=P.|last2=Hestroffer|first2=D.|last3=Cellino|first3=A.|last4=Lattanzi|first4=M.|last5=Martino|first5=M. Di|last6=Zappal\u00e0|first6=V.|date=2003-04-01|title=Asteroid observations with the Hubble Space Telescope FGS|url=https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/abs/2003/14/aa3023/aa3023.html|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|language=en|volume=401|issue=2|pages=733\u2013741|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20030032|issn=0004-6361|bibcode=2003A&A...401..733T}}</ref> Asteroids studied include [[63 Ausonia|(63) Ausonia]],  [[15 Eunomia|(15) Eunomia]], (43) Ariadne, [[44 Nysa|(44) Nysa]], and [[624 Hektor|(624) Hektor]].<ref name=\"Tanga 733\u2013741\"/>\n\n==Trivia==\n* For reasons unknown, \"Asteroid 43 Ariadne\" was included in a list of names of supporters of the [[NASA]] [[spacecraft]] [[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust]] that was stored on a microchip within the spacecraft.\n* The maximum apparent size of Ariadne is equivalent to the maximum apparent size of [[Pluto#Physical characteristics|Pluto]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Carry2012\">{{Citation\n | first1    = B.\n | last1     = Carry\n | title     = Density of asteroids\n | work      = Planetary and Space Science\n | volume    = 73\n | pages      = 98\u2013118\n |date=December 2012\n | doi       = 10.1016/j.pss.2012.03.009\n | bibcode   = 2012P&SS...73...98C\n | postscript= .\n|arxiv = 1203.4336 }} See Table 1.</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041015112635/http://www.rni.helsinki.fi/~mjk/IcarPIII.pdf shape model deduced from lightcurve]\n* [http://www.edpsciences.org/articles/aa/pdf/2003/14/aa3023.pdf?access=ok bi-lobed shape model from Hubble lightcurves] {{dead link|date=April 2019}}\n* {{AstDys|43}}\n* {{JPL small body}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Minor planets navigator |42 Isis |number=43 |44 Nysa}}\n{{Small Solar System bodies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:000043}}\n[[Category:Flora asteroids]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by Norman Pogson|Ariadne]]\n[[Category:Minor planets named from Greek mythology|Ariadne]]\n[[Category:Named minor planets|Ariadne]]\n[[Category:S-type asteroids (Tholen)]]\n[[Category:Sk-type asteroids (SMASS)]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1857|18570415]]\n", "name_user": "AlanM1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move 