vidovica/200328141 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> [[\u017dep\u010de]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Jo\u0161 13 pozitivnih na koronavirus iz pet gradova u Bosni i Hercegovini |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/jos-13-pozitivnih-na-koronavirus-iz-pet-gradova-u-bosni-i-hercegovini/200330007 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n| align=\"right\"| 29\n| align=\"right\"| 0\n| align=\"right\"| 4\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Total\n! align=\"right\"| 265\n! align=\"right\"| 12\n! align=\"right\"| 6\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\"|{{small|''As of 3 April 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Dnevni izvje\u0161taj za potvr\u0111ene slu\u010dajeve COVID-19 U FBiH |url=https://www.zzjzfbih.ba/dnevni-izvjestaj-za-potvrdene-slucajeve-covid-19-u-fbih/ |website=ZZJZ FBiH }}</ref><ref name=\"covid-19.ba\" />\n|}\n\nAs of 3 April 2020, 7 people from [[Br\u010dko District]] have been infected.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Cases\n! scope=\"col\" | Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" | Recoveries\n|-\n| align=\"left\" style=\"background:#EAECF0\"| [[Br\u010dko District]]\n| align=\"right\"| 7\n| align=\"right\"| 0\n| align=\"right\"| 0\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"|{{small|''As of 3 April 2020}}<ref name=\"Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH\"/>\n|}\n\n==Measures==\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n\nThe [[Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] announced Armed Forces' placement of quarantine tents at the country's borders intended for Bosnian citizens returning home. Every Bosnian citizen arriving to the country is obligated to self-quarantine for 14 days starting from the day of arrival.  Tents will be set up on the northern border with [[Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Dodik: Od ponedeljka vojska izlazi na granicu i postavlja satore za karantin | url= https://faktor.ba/vijest/dodik-od-ponedjeljka-vojska-izlazi-na-granicu-i-postavlja-satore-za-karantin/74164|website=faktor.ba | access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina issued a decision which forbids for foreign nationals entering Bosnia and Herzegovina to enter from areas with intensive transmission of virus coronas, and especially from: Provinces of the PRC (Wuhan), South Korea, Japan, Italy, Iran, France, Romania, Germany, Austria, Spain, Switzerland and Belgium.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vije\u0107e ministara BiH: Zabranjen ulazak strancima iz podru\u010dja sa intenzivnom transmisijom korona virusa |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ba/balkan/vije%C4%87e-ministara-bih-zabranjen-ulazak-strancima-iz-podru%C4%8Dja-sa-intenzivnom-transmisijom-korona-virusa/1767130 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina issued a decision which bans entrance for all foreigners, and also from 30 March 2020 all borders at [[List of airports in Bosnia and Herzegovina|airports in Bosnia and Herzegovina]] will be closed for passengers, and airplanes could land only to deliver [[cargo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vije\u0107e ministara BiH odlu\u010dilo: Privremeno se zatvaraju aerodromi za putnike u Bosni i Hercegovini |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/vijece-ministara-bih-odlucilo-privremeno-se-zatvaraju-aerodromi-za-putnike-u-bosni-i-hercegovini/200324142 |website=Klix.ba |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n\n===Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n[[File:Triage tent Sarajevo.jpg|thumb|[[Triage]] tent located in Sarajevo during coronavirus pandemic.]]\nOn 11 March, the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], had enacted a 2-week shutdown of all schools, high schools and universities in order to contain the spread of the virus,<ref>{{cite web |title=Na dvije sedmice se obustavlja nastava u \u0161kolama i na fakultetima u FBiH |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/na-dvije-sedmice-se-obustavlja-nastava-u-skolama-i-na-fakultetima-u-fbih/200311085 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> which was later prolonged by all cantons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nastava u Tuzlanskom kantonu \u0107e biti obustavljena do daljnjeg zbog koronavirusa |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/nastava-u-tuzlanskom-kantonu-ce-biti-obustavljena-do-daljnjeg-zbog-koronavirusa/200326239 |website=Klix.ba |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina already had acts of profiteering. Fines have already been passed to local pharmacies and stores who used this situation and high demand for anti-bacterial gels/sprays and surgical masks. They lifted the prices as much as 3 times of the usual price.<ref>{{cite web | title= Apoteci u Sarajevu 10000km kazne zbog trostruko visih cijena|url=https://www.nesradio.com/novo/vijesti/novosti/Apoteci-u-Sarajevu-10000-KM-kazne-zbog-trostruko-visih-cijena/10723}}</ref> Federal inspection has given out fines in the sum of 43.500&nbsp;km (~22.000 Euros).<ref>{{cite web| title=BiH: Tr\u017ei\u0161ni inspektori izrekli 16 kazni zbog podizanja cijena|url=https://www.slobodnaevropa.org/a/30488933.html}}</ref>\n[[File:Makeshift hand sanitizers.jpg|thumb|One of many [[hand sanitizer]]s attached to a lamp post in [[Visoko]]]]\nThe Headquarters of Federation of B&H issued on 18 March an order that banned all public gatherings, suspending the operation of all catering facilities for the preparation and sale of food and beverages, restaurants, pizzerias, confectioneries, beauty salons, hookah bars, coffee bars, discos, tea shops, cafes, private dentists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro\u010ditajte naredbe: Zabranjuje se rad kafi\u0107a, objekata za masovno okupljanje... |url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a417173/Procitajte-naredbe-Zabranjuje-se-rad-kafica-objekata-za-masovno-okupljanje.html |website=N1 BA |accessdate=18 March 2020 |language=bs-Latn-BA}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |title=Covid-19.ba |url=https://covid-19.ba/dokumenti/civilna_zastita |website=covid-19.ba}}</ref>\n\nSome cities, such as [[Visoko]], installed [[hand sanitizer]]s through the city, in addition to frequent overnight disinfection of streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visoko-rtv.ba/jkpvisoko-zavrsena-dezinfekcija-u-gradu-visoko/|title=JKP\"VISOKO\": ZAVR\u0160ENA DEZINFEKCIJA U GRADU VISOKO|last=Redakcija|date=2020-03-19|website=RTV VISOKO|language=bs-BA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a416511/Visoko-Pocelo-postavljanje-dozatora-na-javnim-povrsinama-za-dezinfekciju-ruku.html|title=Visoko: Po\u010delo postavljanje dozatora na javnim povr\u0161inama za dezinfekciju ruku|website=N1 BA|language=bs-Latn-BA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe civil protection service of Federation of B&H on 20 March 2020 issued an order, which banned the movement of people under the age of 18 and over 65 in the Federation of BiH.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zabrana kretanja osobama mla\u0111im od 18 godina i starijim od 65 u FBiH |url=https://www.slobodnaevropa.org/a/30499978.html |website=Radio Slobodna Evropa |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=sh}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2020, a [[curfew]] was introduced for the entire Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina every day from 18:00 until 05:00, and its implementation started on 22 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Federalni \u0161tab donio naredbu: Od sutra nave\u010der zabrana kretanja od 18 do 5 sati |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/federalni-stab-donio-naredbu-od-sutra-navecer-zabrana-kretanja-od-18-do-5-sati/200321099 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> On 29 March 2020, time for curfew was changed to 20:00 until 05:00.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Republika Srpska===\n[[File:Coronavirus street desinfection in Doboj.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus street disinfection in [[Doboj]].]]\n[[Republika Srpska]] was first to implement measures, beginning from cities of [[Banja Luka]] and [[Doboj]], where business hours were either limited or all business completely forbidden. The Ministry of Health and Social Security ordered the disinfection of all public spaces and property.<ref>{{cite web | title=Ministar zdravlja naredio dezinfekciju svih javnih objekata i povrsina u rs| url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/ministar-zdravlja-naredio-dezinfekciju-svih-javnih-objekata-i-povrsina-u-rs-u/200314046|language=sr-SR}}</ref> Student dormitories in the city of Banja Luka were evacuated for immediate disinfection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iseljavaju se studentski domovi u Banja Luci|url=https://www.nezavisne.com/novosti/drustvo/Iseljavaju-se-studentski-domovi-u-Banjaluci/588914|language=sr-SR}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2020, Republika Srpska had officially enacted a ban on all public gatherings, shut down all schools, and banned entry to all tourists coming from any of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|COVID-19 infected countries across the world]] in order to contain the spread of the virus within the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bosnia bars entry to travelers from coronavirus-hit countries |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-bosnia/bosnias-serb-region-shuts-schools-bans-public-gatherings-over-coronavirus-idUSKBN20X2CA |website=Reuters |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBetween 12 and 13 March, numerous cities have made decisions to limit the work of grocery stores, restaurants, caf\u00e9s and completely limit the work of gyms and fitness centers. Banja Luka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ba/balkan/banjaluka-uvela-vanredne-mjere-zbog-korona-virusa/1763688|title=Banjaluka uvela vanredne mjere zbog korona virusa|accessdate=Mar 18, 2020}}</ref> [[\u010celinac]], [[Prnjavor, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Prnjavor]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvk3.info/prnjavor-zbog-korona-virusa-skracenje-radnog-vremena-i-zabrana-rada-naredba-stupa-na-snagu-odmah/|title=Prnjavor: Zbog korona virusa skra\u0107enje radnog vremena i zabrana rada; Naredba stupa na snagu odmah (VIDEO)|date=Mar 13, 2020|website=Televizija K3|accessdate=Mar 18, 2020}}</ref> [[Mrkonji\u0107 Grad]] and Doboj<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://doboj.gov.ba/bs/stab-korona/|title=\u0160tab za vanredne situacije: Naredba o regulisanju rada trgovinskih i drugih objekata na teritoriji Grada Doboja|date=Mar 13, 2020|accessdate=Mar 18, 2020}}</ref> are some of the cities that made these restrictions.\n\nOn 15 March, Banja Luka has decided to close all restaurants and caf\u00e9s in the city, with the exception of drugstores, hotels and motels, where drugstores will be working until 22h and hotels will be working until 18h.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banja Luka uvela nove mjere za spre\u010davanje \u0161irenja korona virusa|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ba/balkan/banjaluka-uvela-nove-mjere-za-spre%C4%8Davanje-%C5%A1irenja-korona-virusa/1767145|language=sr-SR}}</ref>\n\nThe Minister of Health and Social Security, Alen \u0160erani\u0107, reported that 2026 people are under surveillance in Republika Srpska. \u0160erani\u0107 also noted that only citizens arriving from abroad would be allowed the virus testing, and [[quarantine]] will be made mandatory.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0160erani\u0107:2026 osoba pod nadzorom u RS. Ne dolazite na samovoljno testiranje.|url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a416687/Seranic-2.026-osoba-pod-nadzorom-u-RS-ne-dolazite-samovoljno-na-testiranje.html|language=sr-SR}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2020, [[curfew]] was introduced in entire Republika Srpska every day from 20:00 until 05:00,<ref>{{cite web |title=Dodik: U RS se od ve\u010deras uvodi policijski sat |url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a418241/Dodik-U-RS-se-od-veceras-uvodi-policijski-sat.html |website=N1 BA |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-Latn-BA}}</ref> and total ban of movement for people older that 65.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vi\u0161kovi\u0107: Ve\u010deras u 20 sati po\u010dinje policijski sat u RS |url=https://bhrt.ba/viskovic-od-danas-zabranjeno-kretanje-za-starije-od-65-godina-a-za-sve-od-20-00-do-5-sati/1117340/ |website=BHRT |language=bs-BA |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2020 the National Assembly declared the state of emergency in Republika Srpska<ref>{{cite web |title=Bosnian Serb region declares state of emergency over coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-bosnia/bosnian-serb-region-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus-idUSKBN21F0OQ |website=Reuters.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>, which came into force on 3 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zrni\u0107: Objavljena odluka o vanrednom stanju u RS |url=https://www.nezavisne.com/novosti/bih/Zrnic-Objavljena-odluka-o-vanrednom-stanju-u-RS/592398 |website=Nezavisne novine |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sr |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Br\u010dko District ===\n\nThe Government of [[Br\u010dko District]] is regularly adopting measures for control and prevention of coronavirus pandemic and publish them on their official website.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH |url=http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/ |website=www.vlada.bdcentral.net |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince 22 March 2020, it is prohibited in Br\u010dko District to gather and move in public places and open or closed public areas in a group of three or more persons throughout the day, and [[curfew]] was introduced in entire Br\u010dko District every day from 21:00 until 05:00.<ref>{{cite web |title=U Br\u010dkom na javnom mjestu zabranjeno kretanje tri i vi\u0161e osoba u grupi |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/u-brckom-na-javnom-mjestu-zabranjeno-kretanje-tri-i-vise-osoba-u-grupi/200322116 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH |url=http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/Publication/Read/donesena-naredba-o-policijskom-casu-u-brckom |website=www.vlada.bdcentral.net |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Empty shelves in store.jpg|thumb|Empty shelves for flour in one store in [[Sarajevo]] as a result of panic buying.]]\nMembers of the Board of the Tourism and Hospitality Group of the Foreign Trade Chamber of Bosnia and Herzegovina have warned that the situation in tourism as a sector sensitive to global disruptions and the emergence of a new coronavirus strain could lead to the collapse of all entities operating in the tourism and hospitality sector.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kako \u0107e COVID-19 uticati na bh. turizam: Masovni otkazi dolazaka! |url=https://radiosarajevo.ba/vijesti/bosna-i-hercegovina/kako-ce-covid-19-uticati-na-bh-turizam-masovni-otkazi-dolazaka/369923 |website=Radio Sarajevo |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 21 March, most of the sports activities were canceled across the entire country, including all football matches in all categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=Odgo\u0111ene utakmice BH Telecom Premijer lige i Kupa BiH |url=https://www.nfsbih.ba/vijesti/nogomet-m/bht-premijer-liga/odgodene-utakmice-bh-telecom-premijer-lige-i-kupa-bih/ |website=www.nfsbih.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-ba}}</ref>\n\n== International aid ==\nThe countries and [[international organization]]s that have sent aid and funds to Bosnia and Herzegovina, to help fight the pandemic:\n\n* {{Flag|EU}} - The EU is considering two ways to assist Bosnia and Herzegovina, including quick support in provision of up to [[Euro|EUR]] 7 million worth of medical equipment and mid-term adjustment and enforcement of EU support in the amount of up to EUR 50 million for the economic development programmes.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU to assist BiH with provision of medical equipment and mitigation of the COVID-19 impact on the economy |url=https://europa.ba/?p=68202 |website=Europa.ba |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} - [[Government of Malaysia]] will send two million protective masks to Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |title=Malezija \u0107e BiH poslati dva miliona za\u0161titnih maski |url=https://bhrt.ba/malezija-ce-bih-poslati-dva-miliona-zastitnih-maski/ |website=BHRT |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=bs-BA |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> \n* {{Flag|Serbia}} - Serbia is assisting Republika Srpska in medicines, protective equipment, and vital clinical machines, and also is assisting entire Bosnia and Herzegovina with food including wheat, corn and soybeans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sastanak sa srpskim \u010dlanom Predsedni\u0161tva Bosne i Hercegovine |url=https://www.predsednik.rs/lat/pres-centar/vesti/sastanak-sa-srpskim-clanom-predsednistva-bosne-i-hercegovine-28779 |website=Predsednik Republike Srbije |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Switzerland}} - On 23 March 2020, Embassy of Switzerland in Bosnia and Herzegovina informed Minister of Security that Switzerland has allocate 200,000 [[USD]] for assistance to Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |title=Na videokonferenciji sa ambasadorima i predstavnicima me\u0111unarodnih organizacija i agencija BiH dobila 7.200.000 eura |url=http://www.msb.gov.ba/vijesti/saopstenja/default.aspx?id=18580&langTag=bs-BA |website=www.msb.gov.ba |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Turkey}} - Turkey sent humanitarian aid on 24 March 2020 that include protective masks, gloves, protective suits and goggles to [[Red Cross Society of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stigla pomo\u0107 iz Turske: Solidarnost sa BiH u te\u0161kim vremenima {{!}} Sarajevo.ba |url=https://www.sarajevo.ba/bs/article/7676/stigla-pomoc-iz-turske-solidarnost-sa-bih-u-teskim-vremenima |website=www.sarajevo.ba |language=bs}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|UN}} - [[United Nations Development Programme]] in Bosnia and Herzegovina urgently financed procurement of 50,000 coronavirus test kits.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bosnia will get 50,000 new coronavirus tests, minister says |url=http://ba.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a418117/Bosnia-will-get-50-000-new-coronavirus-tests-minister-says.html |website=N1 BA |language=bs-Latn-BA}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|USA}} - US Government on 23 March 2020 donated medical materials and other important supplies to the [[Armed Forces of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sarajevo |first1=US Embassy |title=The first batch of humanitarian assistance from the U.S. Government has arrived to assist the citizens of BiH.  Arriving via U.S. military aircraft and donated to the AFBiH were medical materials and other important supplies.pic.twitter.com/P4ePxJaf8i |url=https://twitter.com/USEmbassySJJ/status/1242071446270214144 |website=@USEmbassySJJ |language=en |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]] is donating [[United States dollar|$]]1.2 million to Bosnia and Herzegovina to help its laboratory systems, activate case-finding & monitoring, support experts, bolster awareness & community engagement and strengthen prevention.<ref>{{cite web |title=@USAID is donating $1.2 million to #BiH to help its laboratory systems, activate case-finding & monitoring, support experts, bolster awareness & community engagement and strengthen prevention.  #COVID19  #Coronavirus #USAinBiH @USAIDGH @USAIDMarkGreen @USAIDBGlick @USEmbassySJJpic.twitter.com/Z4gWRK364Q |url=https://twitter.com/USAIDBIH/status/1244528920512409600 |website=@USAIDBIH |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://covid-19.ba/ Official website of Government of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina related to coronavirus pandemic]\n* [https://koronavirususrpskoj.com/ Official website of Government of Republika Srpska related to coronavirus pandemic]\n\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Europe|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Bosnia and Herzegovina|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "name_user": "Smooth O", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Bosnia_and_Herzegovina"}
{"title_page": "Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Short description|Hospital in Alcorc\u00f3n, Spain}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| name        = Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n\n| org/group   = \n| logo        = \n| logo_size   = \n| image       = Alcorc\u00f3n - Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n 2.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = Entrance of the Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n\n| caption     = \n| coordinates = {{coord|40.3488|3.8367|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| location    = [[Alcorc\u00f3n]], [[Community of Madrid]], Spain\n| healthcare  = <!-- UK: NHS; AU/CA: Medicare; ELSE free-form text, e.g. Private -->\n| funding     = \n| type        = \n| affiliation = \n| patron      = \n| network     = \n| standards   = \n| emergency   = \n| beds        = \n| speciality  = \n| helipad     = \n| h1-number   = \n| h1-length-f = \n| h1-length-m = \n| h1-surface  = <!-- up to h12 -->\n| founded     = 1997\n| closed      = \n| demolished  = \n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| other_links = \n| module      = \n}}\nThe '''Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n (HUFA)''' is a major [[Hospital#Types|general hospital]] in [[Alcorc\u00f3n]], a city in the [[Madrid metropolitan area]] of [[Spain]]. It was founded in 1997.<ref name=Guardian2001/>\n\nAlthough the hospital was built by the [[Spanish National Health System]], its operational management is [[contracted out]] to a private company, and is exempt from many of the rules normally imposed on state-owned hospitals. The hospital was allowed to negotiate its own contracts with workers. The governance of the hospital includes local government, trade unions, health workers and community groups.<ref name=Guardian2001>{{cite news|title=Milburn seeks hospital role model in Spain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/nov/06/uk.publicservices|accessdate=17 November 2014|publisher=Guardian|date=6 November 2001|author=John Carvel and Giles Tremlett}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital's organizational structure is thought to have been one of the inspirations behind the creation of the United Kingdom's system of [[NHS Foundation Trust]]s.<ref name=Guardian2001/>\n\nIn October 2014, the hospital was reported to be treating a case of [[Ebola virus disease]] under strict biosecurity precautions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/07/ebola-europe-unavoidable-who-spain|title=Ebola unavoidable in Europe, says WHO as Spain rushes to contain case|author=Sarah Boseley|date=8 October 2014|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.es/sociedad/20141006/abci-alcorcon-protocolo-ebola-201410061836.html|title=El Hospital de Alcorc\u00f3n activa el protocolo de seguridad por un caso de \u00e9bola|publisher=ABC.es|date=2014-10-06|language=Spanish}}</ref> The patient, [[Maria Teresa Romero Ramos]], had arrived at the hospital by ambulance on October 6.<ref name=yardley20141014>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/15/world/europe/spanish-nurse-ebola-health-budget-cuts.html|title=Spain Exposes Holes in Plans to Treat Ebola|date=14 October 2014|author=Jim Yardley|work=New York Times}}</ref> After diagnosis, she was later transferred to the [[Hospital Carlos III]] in Madrid for treatment.<ref>{{cite web|title=La segunda enfermera ingresada da negativo en la prueba del virus|url=http://www.elconfidencial.com/espana/2014-10-07/la-segunda-enfermera-ingresada-da-negativo-en-la-prueba-del-virus_229489/|date=2014-10-07|publisher=El Confidencial|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=yardley20141014/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in the Community of Madrid]]\n[[Category:Teaching hospitals in Spain]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Health facilities that treated Ebola patients]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1997]]\n \n\n{{spain-struct-stub}}\n{{Europe-hospital-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Hospital in Alcorc\u00f3n, Spain}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| name        = Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n\n| org/group   = \n| logo        = \n| logo_size   = \n| image       = Alcorc\u00f3n - Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n 2.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = Entrance of the Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n\n| caption     = \n| coordinates = {{coord|40.3488|3.8367|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| location    = [[Alcorc\u00f3n]], [[Community of Madrid]], Spain\n| healthcare  = <!-- UK: NHS; AU/CA: Medicare; ELSE free-form text, e.g. Private -->\n| funding     = \n| type        = \n| affiliation = \n| patron      = \n| network     = \n| standards   = \n| emergency   = \n| beds        = \n| speciality  = \n| helipad     = \n| h1-number   = \n| h1-length-f = \n| h1-length-m = \n| h1-surface  = <!-- up to h12 -->\n| founded     = 1997\n| closed      = \n| demolished  = \n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| other_links = \n| module      = \n}}\nThe '''Hospital Universitario Fundaci\u00f3n Alcorc\u00f3n (HUFA)''' is a major [[Hospital#Types|general hospital]] in [[Alcorc\u00f3n]], a city in the [[Madrid metropolitan area]] of [[Spain]]. It was founded in 1997.<ref name=Guardian2001/>\n\nAlthough the hospital was built by the [[Spanish National Health System]], its operational management is [[contracted out]] to a private company, and is exempt from many of the rules normally imposed on state-owned hospitals. The hospital was allowed to negotiate its own contracts with workers. The governance of the hospital includes local government, trade unions, health workers and community groups.<ref name=Guardian2001>{{cite news|title=Milburn seeks hospital role model in Spain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/nov/06/uk.publicservices|accessdate=17 November 2014|publisher=Guardian|date=6 November 2001|author=John Carvel and Giles Tremlett}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital's organizational structure is thought to have been one of the inspirations behind the creation of the United Kingdom's system of [[NHS Foundation Trust]]s.<ref name=Guardian2001/>\n\nIn October 2014, the hospital was reported to be treating a case of [[Ebola virus disease]] under strict biosecurity precautions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/07/ebola-europe-unavoidable-who-spain|title=Ebola unavoidable in Europe, says WHO as Spain rushes to contain case|author=Sarah Boseley|date=8 October 2014|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.es/sociedad/20141006/abci-alcorcon-protocolo-ebola-201410061836.html|title=El Hospital de Alcorc\u00f3n activa el protocolo de seguridad por un caso de \u00e9bola|publisher=ABC.es|date=2014-10-06|language=Spanish}}</ref> The patient, [[Maria Teresa Romero Ramos]], had arrived at the hospital by ambulance on October 6.<ref name=yardley20141014>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/15/world/europe/spanish-nurse-ebola-health-budget-cuts.html|title=Spain Exposes Holes in Plans to Treat Ebola|date=14 October 2014|author=Jim Yardley|work=New York Times}}</ref> After diagnosis, she was later transferred to the [[Hospital Carlos III]] in Madrid for treatment.<ref>{{cite web|title=La segunda enfermera ingresada da negativo en la prueba del virus|url=http://www.elconfidencial.com/espana/2014-10-07/la-segunda-enfermera-ingresada-da-negativo-en-la-prueba-del-virus_229489/|date=2014-10-07|publisher=El Confidencial|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=yardley20141014/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in the Community of Madrid]]\n[[Category:Teaching hospitals in Spain]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Health facilities that treated Ebola patients]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1997]]\n \n\n{{spain-struct-stub}}\n{{Europe-hospital-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Morris Schaffer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added Commons category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital_Universitario_Fundaci%C3%B3n_Alcorc%C3%B3n"}
{"title_page": "Michael (2011 Indian film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2011 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Michael\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Ribhu Dasgupta]]\n| producer       = [[Anurag Kashyap]]\n| writer         = Ribhu Dasgupta<br>[[Debaloy Bhattacharya]]\n| starring       = [[Naseeruddin Shah]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Somak Mukherjee\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2011|9|15|[[2011 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Michael''''' is a 2011 Indian  [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Ribhu Dasgupta]] and produced by [[Anurag Kashyap]].<ref>{{cite book |title=International Film Guide 2012 |first=Ian Hayden |last=Smith |year= 2012 |isbn= 978-1908215017 |page= 141}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonbanglaradio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonbanglaradio.com/content/93286811-interview-film-maker-ribhu-dasgupta-michael-hindi-2011-directorial-debut-premiering |title=Interview: Film-Maker Ribhu Dasgupta on ''Michael'' (Hindi, 2011) - Directorial Debut Premiering in TIFF 2011 |accessdate=28 August 2012 |work=washingtonbanglaradio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/michael-movie-trailer-naseeruddin-shah-looks-dark-and-grungy |title=''Michael'' movie trailer: Naseeruddin Shah looks dark and grungy |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe film opens some years ago with Kolkata police inspector Michael at a political rally. It is a large rally, several hundred people packed into a square, the largest protest against the current government, yet it is wholly peaceful. Michael receives a radio order to open fire and disperse the crowd. He protests, it is a peaceful rally, but his supervisor, acting on political pressure from above, repeats the order to fire. Michael fires a single shot that accidentally hits a 12-year-old boy.\n\nMichael is diagnosed with \"progressive myopia\" and subsequently fired from his position without severance or pension benefits. He begins receiving angry phone calls from the father of the dead boy. The father threatens to kill Michael's 8-year-old son Roy on his 12th birthday.\n\nA couple of years later Michael is living in a small apartment with his son. He makes a miserable living as a projectionist in a movie theater and ekes out some additional income pirating movies for a gang of local thugs. Michael is always harangued by his landlord, the drunk and bitter Mr. DCosta, and continues to receive progressively more threatening calls from the dead boy's father. His only goal is to get his son out of the city and into a boarding school. Rwitika, his only friend, occasionally looks after Roy and urges Michael to pick up and move on. The landlord DCosta frequently bullies and browbeats Michael for overdue rent. Michael is saving furiously to send Roy away and moves the money about his apartment so DCosta cannot find it. Amid this turmoil he finds a quiet comfort in Mrs DCosta who generally sympathizes with him and occasionally warns him if DCosta is about to go on the warpath.\n\nA few days before Roy's 12th birthday Michael gets intensely threatening phone calls. He stumbles out of his movie theater (and forgets an important movie copying job for which he has received an advance). His midget assistant Makkhan copies the movie and tries to sell it to a rival gang. Michael returns later and picks up a DVD (empty, since Makkhan took the movie DVD) and delivers it. When Michael returns home he finds his money gone and the gang boys outside who beat him up until he figures out what happened. His assistant Makkhan shows up, badly beaten up, and discloses that the rival gang members took the DVD and beat him up and gave him no money. If Michael had paid him more money he would not have gone to the other gang. They argue about the money until Michael discovers that his money is gone! Michael, slowly unspooling into insanity, moves Roy to Rwitika's place and subsequently beseeches her to send him away. He barges into DCosta's flat, across the hall, to see them celebrating something. In a maddened (and drunk) stupor Michael threatens DCosta with a pistol and later begs him to return the money. DCosta, himself drunk, curses and berates Michael whereupon Michael, crazed with anger, shoots DCosta dead! His wife reveals that it was she who took the money for her fertility treatment. Michael is shocked and hurt that she betrayed his trust. He runs out of the flat and, knowing that the police will hunt him down for murder, goes to get Roy out of the city.\n\nMichael hurries to Rwitika's place to get Roy. It is midnight, Roy's birthday. Michael runs across a crossroad. A public phone rings, Michael stops to pick it up, it is the dead boy's father, he will shoot Roy! Michael begs him to stop ... Rwitika comes on the line next! Michael hangs up the phone and steps into the road when a passing taxicab runs him over and kills him. It is revealed that Michael had been hearing voices all along (there was no father of the dead boy) and his guilt over the boy at the rally slowly drove him insane. The film ends as a police jeep finds his body and calls for an ambulance.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Naseeruddin Shah]] as Michael\n* [[Mahie Gill]] as Rwitika\n* [[Sabyasachi Chakrabarty]]\n* [[Rudranil Ghosh]]\n* [[Irawati Harshe]]\n* [[Churni Ganguly]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1754202|Michael}}\n\n{{Anurag Kashyap|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Michael}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:2011 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2011 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Michael\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Ribhu Dasgupta]]\n| producer       = [[Anurag Kashyap]]\n| writer         = Ribhu Dasgupta<br>[[Debaloy Bhattacharya]]\n| starring       = [[Naseeruddin Shah]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Somak Mukherjee\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2011|9|15|[[2011 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Michael''''' is a 2011 Indian  [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Ribhu Dasgupta]] and produced by [[Anurag Kashyap]].<ref>{{cite book |title=International Film Guide 2012 |first=Ian Hayden |last=Smith |year= 2012 |isbn= 978-1908215017 |page= 141}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonbanglaradio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonbanglaradio.com/content/93286811-interview-film-maker-ribhu-dasgupta-michael-hindi-2011-directorial-debut-premiering |title=Interview: Film-Maker Ribhu Dasgupta on ''Michael'' (Hindi, 2011) - Directorial Debut Premiering in TIFF 2011 |accessdate=28 August 2012 |work=washingtonbanglaradio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/michael-movie-trailer-naseeruddin-shah-looks-dark-and-grungy |title=''Michael'' movie trailer: Naseeruddin Shah looks dark and grungy |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe film opens some years ago with Kolkata police inspector Michael at a political rally. It is a large rally, several hundred people packed into a square, the largest protest against the current government, yet it is wholly peaceful. Michael receives a radio order to open fire and disperse the crowd. He protests, it is a peaceful rally, but his supervisor, acting on political pressure from above, repeats the order to fire. Michael fires a single shot that accidentally hits a 12-year-old boy.\n\nMichael is diagnosed with \"progressive myopia\" and subsequently fired from his position without severance or pension benefits. He begins receiving angry phone calls from the father of the dead boy. The father threatens to kill Michael's 8-year-old son Roy on his 12th birthday.\n\nA couple of years later Michael is living in a small apartment with his son. He makes a miserable living as a projectionist in a movie theater and ekes out some additional income pirating movies for a gang of local thugs. Michael is always harangued by his landlord, the drunk and bitter Mr. DCosta, and continues to receive progressively more threatening calls from the dead boy's father. His only goal is to get his son out of the city and into a boarding school. Rwitika, his only friend, occasionally looks after Roy and urges Michael to pick up and move on. The landlord DCosta frequently bullies and browbeats Michael for overdue rent. Michael is saving furiously to send Roy away and moves the money about his apartment so DCosta cannot find it. Amid this turmoil he finds a quiet comfort in Mrs DCosta who generally sympathizes with him and occasionally warns him if DCosta is about to go on the warpath.\n\nA few days before Roy's 12th birthday Michael gets intensely threatening phone calls. He stumbles out of his movie theater (and forgets an important movie copying job for which he has received an advance). His midget assistant Makkhan copies the movie and tries to sell it to a rival gang. Michael returns later and picks up a DVD (empty, since Makkhan took the movie DVD) and delivers it. When Michael returns home he finds his money gone and the gang boys outside who beat him up until he figures out what happened. His assistant Makkhan shows up, badly beaten up, and discloses that the rival gang members took the DVD and beat him up and gave him no money. If Michael had paid him more money he would not have gone to the other gang. They argue about the money until Michael discovers that his money is gone! Michael, slowly unspooling into insanity, moves Roy to Rwitika's place and subsequently beseeches her to send him away. He barges into DCosta's flat, across the hall, to see them celebrating something. In a maddened (and drunk) stupor Michael threatens DCosta with a pistol and later begs him to return the money. DCosta, himself drunk, curses and berates Michael whereupon Michael, crazed with anger, shoots DCosta dead! His wife reveals that it was she who took the money for her fertility treatment. Michael is shocked and hurt that she betrayed his trust. He runs out of the flat and, knowing that the police will hunt him down for murder, goes to get Roy out of the city.\n\nMichael hurries to Rwitika's place to get Roy. It is midnight, Roy's birthday. Michael runs across a crossroad. A public phone rings, Michael stops to pick it up, it is the dead boy's father, he will shoot Roy! Michael begs him to stop ... Rwitika comes on the line next! Michael hangs up the phone and steps into the road when a passing taxicab runs him over and kills him. It is revealed that Michael had been hearing voices all along (there was no father of the dead boy) and his guilt over the boy at the rally slowly drove him insane. The film ends as a police jeep finds his body and calls for an ambulance.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Naseeruddin Shah]] as Michael\n* [[Mahie Gill]] as Rwitika\n* [[Sabyasachi Chakrabarty]]\n* [[Rudranil Ghosh]]\n* [[Irawati Harshe]]\n* [[Churni Ganguly]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1754202|Michael}}\n\n{{Anurag Kashyap|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Michael}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:2011 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_(2011_Indian_film)"}
{"title_page": "The Tower of Babel (Bruegel)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file=Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (Vienna) - Google Art Project - edited.jpg\n| title=The (Great) Tower of Babel\n| medium=oil on wood panel\n| artist=Pieter Bruegel the Elder\n| year=c. 1563\n| height_metric=114\n| width_metric=155\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| city=[[Vienna]]\n| museum=[[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file=Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (Rotterdam) - Google Art Project - edited.jpg\n| title=The (Little) Tower of Babel\n| artist=Pieter Bruegel the Elder\n| year=c. 1563\n| medium=oil on wood panel\n| height_metric=60\n| width_metric=74.5\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| city=[[Rotterdam]]\n| museum=[[Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]]\n}}\n'''''The Tower of Babel''''' was the subject of three paintings by [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]]. The first, a miniature painted on ivory, was painted while Bruegel was in Rome and is now lost.<ref>Orenstein, 6, one of the works belonging to [[Giulio Clovio]]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Morra|first=Joanne|title=Utopia Lost: Allegory, Ruins and Pieter Bruegel\u2019s Towers of Babel|journal=Art History|year=2007|volume=30|issue=2|pages=200|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8365.2007.00538.x}}</ref> The two surviving paintings, often distinguished by the prefix \"Great\" and \"Little\", are in the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], [[Vienna]] and the [[Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]] in [[Rotterdam]] respectively.  Both are [[oil painting]]s on wood panels.\n\nThe Rotterdam painting is about half the size of the Vienna one. In broad terms they have exactly the same composition, but at a detailed level everything is different, whether in the architecture of the tower or in the sky and the landscape around the tower.  The Vienna version has a group in the foreground, with the main figure presumably [[Nimrod]], who was believed to have ordered the construction of the tower,<ref name=\"Art and the Bible\" /> although the Bible does not actually say this.  In Vienna the tower rises at the edge of a large city, but the Rotterdam tower is in open countryside. \n\nThe paintings depict the construction of the [[Tower of Babel]], which, according to the [[Book of Genesis]] in the [[Bible]], was built by a unified, [[Confusion of tongues|monolingual]] humanity as a mark of their achievement and to prevent them from scattering: \"Then they said, 'Come, let us build ourselves a city, and a tower with its top in the heavens, and let us make a name for ourselves; otherwise we shall be scattered abroad upon the face of the whole earth.'\" (Genesis 11:4).\n\n==Description and analysis==\nBruegel's depiction of the architecture of the tower, with its numerous arches and other examples of [[Roman engineering]], is deliberately reminiscent of the Roman [[Colosseum]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Malam|first=John|title=Pieter Bruegel|year=1999|publisher=Carolrhoda Books|isbn=1-57505-366-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/pieterbreugel0000mala/page/15 15]|url=https://archive.org/details/pieterbreugel0000mala/page/15}}</ref> which Christians of the time saw as a symbol of both hubris and persecution. Bruegel had visited [[Rome]] in 1552\u20131553. Back in [[Antwerp]], he may have refreshed his memory of Rome with a series of engravings of the principal landmarks of the city made by the publisher of his own prints, [[Hieronymous Cock]], for he incorporated details of Cock's engravings of Roman views in both surviving versions of the ''Tower of Babel''.  \n\nThe parallel of Rome and [[Babylon]] had a particular significance for Bruegel's contemporaries: Rome was the Eternal City, intended by the [[Caesar (title)|Caesars]] to last forever, and its decay and ruin were taken to symbolize the vanity and transience of earthly efforts.<ref name=\"Art and the Bible\">{{cite web|title=The Tower of Babel|url=http://www.artbible.info/art/tower-of-babel.html|work=Art and the Bible|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref> The Tower was also symbolic of the religious turmoil between the [[Catholic Church]] (which at the time conducted all services in Latin) and the polyglot Protestant religion that was increasingly popular in the [[Netherlands]].  The subject may have had a specific topicality, as the famous [[Plantin Polyglot|Polyglot Bible]] in six languages, a landmark in Biblical scholarship, was published in Antwerp in 1566.<ref>Snyder, 502</ref>  Although at first glance the tower appears to be a stable series of concentric pillars, upon closer examination it is apparent that none of the layers lies at a true horizontal. Rather the tower is built as an ascending spiral.\n\nThe workers in the painting have built the [[arch]]es perpendicular to the slanted ground, thereby making them unstable, and a few arches can already be seen crumbling. The foundation and bottom layers of the tower had not been completed before the higher layers were constructed.\n[[File:La Tour de Babel, Van Valckenborch, 1594.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Van Valckenborch's ''Tower of Babel'' 1594]]\n[[Lucas van Valckenborch]], a contemporary of Bruegel's, also painted the Tower of Babel in the 1560s and later in his career, possibly after seeing Bruegel's depiction.<ref name=\"Art and the Bible\" /> Both were part of a larger tradition of painting the tower during the 16th and 17th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|last=West|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew West (linguist)|title=72 More Views of the Tower of Babel|url=http://babelstone.blogspot.com/2008/12/72-more-views-of-tower-of-babel.html|work=BabelStone|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>  \n[[File:Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (detail) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Detail at right side, with original rock formation.]]\n\nThe story of the [[Tower of Babel]] (like that in [[The Suicide of Saul]], Bruegel's only other painting with an [[Old Testament]] subject) was interpreted as an example of pride punished, and that is no doubt what Bruegel intended his painting to illustrate.<ref>Orenstein, 58</ref> Moreover, the hectic activity of the engineers, masons and workmen points to a second moral: the futility of much human endeavour. [[Nimrod]]'s doomed building was used to illustrate this meaning in [[Sebastian Brant]]'s ''[[Ship of Fools (satire)|Ship of Fools]]''.<ref>This book's online text may be viewed at [http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/20179 ''The Ship of Fools''], [[Project Gutenberg]]. See also article by N. Collins, on [http://www.visual-arts-cork.com/famous-paintings/tower-of-babel.htm Encyclopedia of Art Education] Accessed 4 February 2012</ref> Bruegel's knowledge of building procedures and techniques is considerable and correct in detail. The skill with which he has shown these activities recalls that his very last commission, left unfinished at his death, was for a series of documentary paintings recording the digging of a canal linking [[Brussels]] and [[Antwerp]].<ref>P. Allegretti, ''ibid.''</ref>\n\nBoth towers are shown partly-built with stone facings over a massive brick framework, a typical technique in [[Roman architecture]], used in the Colosseum and other huge Roman buildings.  Grand and formal architecture of this sort is not a usual interest of Bruegel in either paintings or drawings, although it was typical subject matter for many of his contemporaries.<ref>Snyder, 502; Orenstein, 96-97</ref>  Nadine Orenstein, in discussing his only known drawing of buildings in Rome, concludes from the details taken from the Colosseum in both ''Tower'' paintings that he \"must\" have recorded them in drawings on his visit ten years before, but given the easy availability of prints this does not seem conclusive.<ref>Orenstein, 96-97; see [http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=712020&partId=1 this British Museum page] for another drawing of Roman ruins, perhaps the Colosseum, recently attributed to Bruegel</ref>\n\nThere are no surviving drawings that are studies for this or any other of Bruegel's paintings. This is despite indications that Bruegel did make use of preparatory studies. Both ''Tower'' versions are full of the type of details which are likely to have been worked out in sketches first.<ref>Orenstein, 30-31</ref>  Except for a lack of mountains, the paintings contain the main ingredients of the [[world landscape]], a type of composition followed in many of Bruegel's earlier landscapes.  The Vienna tower is built around a very steep small mountain, which can be seen protruding from the architecture at the centre near the ground and to the right higher up.\n\n==Provenance==\nThe Vienna painting is signed and dated \"Brvegel. FE. M.CCCCC.LXIII \", on the stone block directly in front of the king.  It was painted in 1563 for the Antwerp banker [[Nicolaes Jonghelinck]],<ref name=\"khm\">{{cite web |url=http://bilddatenbank.khm.at/viewArtefact?id=323 |title=KHM Bilddatenbank |accessdate=2011-09-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103131309/http://bilddatenbank.khm.at/viewArtefact?id=323 |archivedate=November 3, 2012 }}</ref> one of Bruegel's best patrons, who owned no fewer than 16 of his paintings.<ref>Orenstein, 8</ref>\n\n==Gallery of details (Vienna version)==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Hieronymus_Cock_-_Kolosseum_1551_beschnitten.jpg|Print of the [[Colosseum]] in Rome, published by [[Hieronymus Cock]] in 1551\nPieter Bruegel d. \u00c4. 109.jpg|The king and entourage visiting the builders. Bruegel's signature at bottom right.\nGrosser Turmbau zu Babel - Ausschnitt 2.jpg|The peak above the clouds\nGrosser Turmbau zu Babel - Ausschnitt 3.jpg|Sillouetted bricklayers at the top level\nTretkran (Bruegel).jpg|A crane\nPieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (detail) - WGA3415.jpg|[[Vault (architecture)|Vault]] with [[falsework]]\n</gallery>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\nThe painting appears as the main element on one box art design of the video game ''[[Civilization III]]''.\n\nThey are briefly mentioned in ''[[Shadow Man (video game)|Shadowman]]'', where Jaunty explains that Bruegel was shocked at how The Asylum resembled his paintings.\n\nThe painting also makes an appearance in the 2012 video game, ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops 2]]'', in the zombie survival mode in the map, 'Green Run' on a wall in a section of the map (Town). \n\nThe painting is also featured on the cover of Paul Graham's 2004 book, [[Hackers & Painters]].\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right\n | headerimage=[[File:Pieter Bruegel d. \u00c4. 109.jpg|210px]]\n | video1 = [http://smarthistory.khanacademy.org/bruegels-tower-of-babel.html Bruegel's ''Tower of Babel''], [[Smarthistory]]<ref name=\"smarth\">{{cite web | title =Bruegel's Tower of Babel | work = | publisher =[[Smarthistory]] at [[Khan Academy]] | date = | url =http://smarthistory.khanacademy.org/bruegels-tower-of-babel.html | accessdate =March 12, 2013 }}</ref> }}The 2016 video game ''Let it Die'' features a homage to the painting. Showing the in-game 'Tower of Barbs' with nearly identical features as the original work with a modern urban motif and Death standing in place of King Nimrod.\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right\n | headerimage=[[File:Bruegel_d._\u00c4.,_Pieter_-_Tower_of_Babel_-_Museum_Boijmans_Van_Beuningen_Rotterdam.jpg|210px]]\n | video1 = [http://www.arttube.nl/videos/de-toren-van-babel ''The \"Little\" Tower of Babel''], ARTtube<ref name=\"arttube\">{{cite web | title =The \"Little\" Tower of Babel | work = | publisher =[[ARTtube]] | date = | url =http://arttube.nl/en/video/Boijmans/Pieter_Brueghel | accessdate =March 19, 2013 }}</ref> Dutch language}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tower of Babel (M. C. Escher)|''Tower of Babel'' (M. C. Escher)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{Cite book|title= Pieter Bruegel the Elder: Drawings and Prints|last=Orenstein|first=Nadine M., ed.|year=2001|publisher=[[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|isbn=9780870999901 | url=http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/97318}} (full text free online)\n*[[James Snyder (art historian)|Snyder, James]]. ''Northern Renaissance Art'', 1985, Harry N. Abrams, {{ISBN|0136235964}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Tower of Babel by Pieter Bruegel the Elder}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121103131309/http://bilddatenbank.khm.at/viewArtefact?id=323 ''The Tower'' at the KHM]\n*[http://collectie.boijmans.nl/en/work/2443%20%28OK%29 ''The \"Little\" Tower of Babel'' at Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]\n\n{{Paintings by Pieter Bruegel (I)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tower of Babel, The}}\n[[Category:1560s paintings]]\n[[Category:Dutch paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\n[[category:Paintings of the Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]]\n[[Category:Paintings depicting figures from the Book of Genesis]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Pieter Brueghel the Elder]]\n[[Category:Tower of Babel]]\n[[Category:Architecture paintings]]\n[[Category:Tower of Babel in art]]\n[[Category:1563 paintings]]\n[[Category:Nimrod]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file=Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (Vienna) - Google Art Project - edited.jpg\n| title=The (Great) Tower of Babel\n| medium=oil on wood panel\n| artist=Pieter Bruegel the Elder\n| year=c. 1563\n| height_metric=114\n| width_metric=155\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| city=[[Vienna]]\n| museum=[[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file=Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (Rotterdam) - Google Art Project - edited.jpg\n| title=The (Little) Tower of Babel\n| artist=Pieter Bruegel the Elder\n| year=c. 1563\n| medium=oil on wood panel\n| height_metric=60\n| width_metric=74.5\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| city=[[Rotterdam]]\n| museum=[[Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]]\n}}\n'''''The Tower of Babel''''' was the subject of three paintings by [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]]. The first, a miniature painted on ivory, was painted while Bruegel was in Rome and is now lost.<ref>Orenstein, 6, one of the works belonging to [[Giulio Clovio]]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Morra|first=Joanne|title=Utopia Lost: Allegory, Ruins and Pieter Bruegel\u2019s Towers of Babel|journal=Art History|year=2007|volume=30|issue=2|pages=200|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8365.2007.00538.x}}</ref> The two surviving paintings, often distinguished by the prefix \"Great\" and \"Little\", are in the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], [[Vienna]] and the [[Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]] in [[Rotterdam]] respectively.  Both are [[oil painting]]s on wood panels.\n\nThe Rotterdam painting is about half the size of the Vienna one. In broad terms they have exactly the same composition, but at a detailed level everything is different, whether in the architecture of the tower or in the sky and the landscape around the tower.  The Vienna version has a group in the foreground, with the main figure presumably [[Nimrod]], who was believed to have ordered the construction of the tower,<ref name=\"Art and the Bible\" /> although the Bible does not actually say this.  In Vienna the tower rises at the edge of a large city, but the Rotterdam tower is in open countryside. \n\nThe paintings depict the construction of the [[Tower of Babel]], which, according to the [[Book of Genesis]] in the [[Bible]], was built by a unified, [[Confusion of tongues|monolingual]] humanity as a mark of their achievement and to prevent them from scattering: \"Then they said, 'Come, let us build ourselves a city, and a tower with its top in the heavens, and let us make a name for ourselves; otherwise we shall be scattered abroad upon the face of the whole earth.'\" (Genesis 11:4).\n\n==Description and analysis==\nBruegel's depiction of the architecture of the tower, with its numerous arches and other examples of [[Roman engineering]], is deliberately reminiscent of the Roman [[Colosseum]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Malam|first=John|title=Pieter Bruegel|year=1999|publisher=Carolrhoda Books|isbn=1-57505-366-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/pieterbreugel0000mala/page/15 15]|url=https://archive.org/details/pieterbreugel0000mala/page/15}}</ref> which Christians of the time saw as a symbol of both hubris and persecution. Bruegel had visited [[Rome]] in 1552\u20131553. Back in [[Antwerp]], he may have refreshed his memory of Rome with a series of engravings of the principal landmarks of the city made by the publisher of his own prints, [[Hieronymous Cock]], for he incorporated details of Cock's engravings of Roman views in both surviving versions of the ''Tower of Babel''.  \n\nThe parallel of Rome and [[Babylon]] had a particular significance for Bruegel's contemporaries: Rome was the Eternal City, intended by the [[Caesar (title)|Caesars]] to last forever, and its decay and ruin were taken to symbolize the vanity and transience of earthly efforts.<ref name=\"Art and the Bible\">{{cite web|title=The Tower of Babel|url=http://www.artbible.info/art/tower-of-babel.html|work=Art and the Bible|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref> The Tower was also symbolic of the religious turmoil between the [[Catholic church]] (which at the time conducted all services in Latin) and the polyglot Protestant religion that was increasingly popular in the [[Netherlands]].  The subject may have had a specific topicality, as the famous [[Plantin Polyglot|Polyglot Bible]] in six languages, a landmark in Biblical scholarship, was published in Antwerp in 1566.<ref>Snyder, 502</ref>  Although at first glance the tower appears to be a stable series of concentric pillars, upon closer examination it is apparent that none of the layers lies at a true horizontal. Rather the tower is built as an ascending spiral.\n\nThe workers in the painting have built the [[arch]]es perpendicular to the slanted ground, thereby making them unstable, and a few arches can already be seen crumbling. The foundation and bottom layers of the tower had not been completed before the higher layers were constructed.\n[[File:La Tour de Babel, Van Valckenborch, 1594.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Van Valckenborch's ''Tower of Babel'' 1594]]\n[[Lucas van Valckenborch]], a contemporary of Bruegel's, also painted the Tower of Babel in the 1560s and later in his career, possibly after seeing Bruegel's depiction.<ref name=\"Art and the Bible\" /> Both were part of a larger tradition of painting the tower during the 16th and 17th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|last=West|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew West (linguist)|title=72 More Views of the Tower of Babel|url=http://babelstone.blogspot.com/2008/12/72-more-views-of-tower-of-babel.html|work=BabelStone|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>  \n[[File:Pieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (detail) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Detail at right side, with original rock formation.]]\n\nThe story of the [[Tower of Babel]] (like that in [[The Suicide of Saul]], Bruegel's only other painting with an [[Old Testament]] subject) was interpreted as an example of pride punished, and that is no doubt what Bruegel intended his painting to illustrate.<ref>Orenstein, 58</ref> Moreover, the hectic activity of the engineers, masons and workmen points to a second moral: the futility of much human endeavour. [[Nimrod]]'s doomed building was used to illustrate this meaning in [[Sebastian Brant]]'s ''[[Ship of Fools (satire)|Ship of Fools]]''.<ref>This book's online text may be viewed at [http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/20179 ''The Ship of Fools''], [[Project Gutenberg]]. See also article by N. Collins, on [http://www.visual-arts-cork.com/famous-paintings/tower-of-babel.htm Encyclopedia of Art Education] Accessed 4 February 2012</ref> Bruegel's knowledge of building procedures and techniques is considerable and correct in detail. The skill with which he has shown these activities recalls that his very last commission, left unfinished at his death, was for a series of documentary paintings recording the digging of a canal linking [[Brussels]] and [[Antwerp]].<ref>P. Allegretti, ''ibid.''</ref>\n\nBoth towers are shown partly-built with stone facings over a massive brick framework, a typical technique in [[Roman architecture]], used in the Colosseum and other huge Roman buildings.  Grand and formal architecture of this sort is not a usual interest of Bruegel in either paintings or drawings, although it was typical subject matter for many of his contemporaries.<ref>Snyder, 502; Orenstein, 96-97</ref>  Nadine Orenstein, in discussing his only known drawing of buildings in Rome, concludes from the details taken from the Colosseum in both ''Tower'' paintings that he \"must\" have recorded them in drawings on his visit ten years before, but given the easy availability of prints this does not seem conclusive.<ref>Orenstein, 96-97; see [http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=712020&partId=1 this British Museum page] for another drawing of Roman ruins, perhaps the Colosseum, recently attributed to Bruegel</ref>\n\nThere are no surviving drawings that are studies for this or any other of Bruegel's paintings. This is despite indications that Bruegel did make use of preparatory studies. Both ''Tower'' versions are full of the type of details which are likely to have been worked out in sketches first.<ref>Orenstein, 30-31</ref>  Except for a lack of mountains, the paintings contain the main ingredients of the [[world landscape]], a type of composition followed in many of Bruegel's earlier landscapes.  The Vienna tower is built around a very steep small mountain, which can be seen protruding from the architecture at the centre near the ground and to the right higher up.\n\n==Provenance==\nThe Vienna painting is signed and dated \"Brvegel. FE. M.CCCCC.LXIII \", on the stone block directly in front of the king.  It was painted in 1563 for the Antwerp banker [[Nicolaes Jonghelinck]],<ref name=\"khm\">{{cite web |url=http://bilddatenbank.khm.at/viewArtefact?id=323 |title=KHM Bilddatenbank |accessdate=2011-09-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103131309/http://bilddatenbank.khm.at/viewArtefact?id=323 |archivedate=November 3, 2012 }}</ref> one of Bruegel's best patrons, who owned no fewer than 16 of his paintings.<ref>Orenstein, 8</ref>\n\n==Gallery of details (Vienna version)==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Hieronymus_Cock_-_Kolosseum_1551_beschnitten.jpg|Print of the [[Colosseum]] in Rome, published by [[Hieronymus Cock]] in 1551\nPieter Bruegel d. \u00c4. 109.jpg|The king and entourage visiting the builders. Bruegel's signature at bottom right.\nGrosser Turmbau zu Babel - Ausschnitt 2.jpg|The peak above the clouds\nGrosser Turmbau zu Babel - Ausschnitt 3.jpg|Sillouetted bricklayers at the top level\nTretkran (Bruegel).jpg|A crane\nPieter Bruegel the Elder - The Tower of Babel (detail) - WGA3415.jpg|[[Vault (architecture)|Vault]] with [[falsework]]\n</gallery>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\nThe painting appears as the main element on one box art design of the video game ''[[Civilization III]]''.\n\nThey are briefly mentioned in ''[[Shadow Man (video game)|Shadowman]]'', where Jaunty explains that Bruegel was shocked at how The Asylum resembled his paintings.\n\nThe painting also makes an appearance in the 2012 video game, ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops 2]]'', in the zombie survival mode in the map, 'Green Run' on a wall in a section of the map (Town). \n\nThe painting is also featured on the cover of Paul Graham's 2004 book, [[Hackers & Painters]].\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right\n | headerimage=[[File:Pieter Bruegel d. \u00c4. 109.jpg|210px]]\n | video1 = [http://smarthistory.khanacademy.org/bruegels-tower-of-babel.html Bruegel's ''Tower of Babel''], [[Smarthistory]]<ref name=\"smarth\">{{cite web | title =Bruegel's Tower of Babel | work = | publisher =[[Smarthistory]] at [[Khan Academy]] | date = | url =http://smarthistory.khanacademy.org/bruegels-tower-of-babel.html | accessdate =March 12, 2013 }}</ref> }}The 2016 video game ''Let it Die'' features a homage to the painting. Showing the in-game 'Tower of Barbs' with nearly identical features as the original work with a modern urban motif and Death standing in place of King Nimrod.\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right\n | headerimage=[[File:Bruegel_d._\u00c4.,_Pieter_-_Tower_of_Babel_-_Museum_Boijmans_Van_Beuningen_Rotterdam.jpg|210px]]\n | video1 = [http://www.arttube.nl/videos/de-toren-van-babel ''The \"Little\" Tower of Babel''], ARTtube<ref name=\"arttube\">{{cite web | title =The \"Little\" Tower of Babel | work = | publisher =[[ARTtube]] | date = | url =http://arttube.nl/en/video/Boijmans/Pieter_Brueghel | accessdate =March 19, 2013 }}</ref> Dutch language}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tower of Babel (M. C. Escher)|''Tower of Babel'' (M. C. Escher)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{Cite book|title= Pieter Bruegel the Elder: Drawings and Prints|last=Orenstein|first=Nadine M., ed.|year=2001|publisher=[[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|isbn=9780870999901 | url=http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/97318}} (full text free online)\n*[[James Snyder (art historian)|Snyder, James]]. ''Northern Renaissance Art'', 1985, Harry N. Abrams, {{ISBN|0136235964}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Tower of Babel by Pieter Bruegel the Elder}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121103131309/http://bilddatenbank.khm.at/viewArtefact?id=323 ''The Tower'' at the KHM]\n*[http://collectie.boijmans.nl/en/work/2443%20%28OK%29 ''The \"Little\" Tower of Babel'' at Museum Boijmans Van Beuningen]\n\n{{Paintings by Pieter Bruegel (I)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tower of Babel, The}}\n[[Category:1560s paintings]]\n[[Category:Dutch paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings 